<HEADLINE> Singapore Government Says Major Y2K Disruptions  Unlikely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government has
assured the public that major Y2K disruptions are unlikely in
Singapore and it will remain vigilant despite the country is well
prepared for Y2K glitches.
</P>
<P>
The statement, released Thursday by the Inforcomm Development
Authority (IDA) of Singapore, came when countries make their final
round of preparations to deal with the Y2K problem in the days
close to the millennium crossover and public interest in the
millennium bug issue is expected to heighten.
</P>
<P>
IDA reaffirmed that Singapore key government systems and
critical infrastructure service providers in finance, utility,
telecommunications, transportation and healthcare have been ready
since the middle of 1999, ahead of the December 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's National Y2K Spokesman Alan Chan, who is permanent
secretary of the Ministry of Communications and Information
Technology, was quoted as saying that "although we are confident
that major disruptions are unlikely, key government agencies have
nonetheless prepared plans to detect glitches quickly and to take
prompt action to fix them quickly should they occur."
</P>
<P>
"The public can be assured that the Singapore government is
ready in any case," Chan was quoted as stressing.
</P>
<P>
IDA said it has set up a National Y2K Coordination Center Y2KCC)
to monitor the Singapore Y2K situation during the millennium
crossover and will be picking early warning signals from the
International Y2K Cooperation Center's website.
</P>
<P>
Besides monitoring the local and international developments,
the National Y2KCC will keep the public informed on Singapore's
Y2K situation as and when necessary through the mass media as well
as via the National Y2K website, IDA added,
</P>
<P>
IDA also gave out some of the essential services' hotline
numbers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
