<HEADLINE> India Resumes Talks with Hijackers after Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Indian negotiators resumed
talks with the hijackers of the Indian Airlines aircraft at
Kandahar, Afghanistan, after their talks broke down early Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
External Affairs minister Jaswant Singh said, "resumption of
the dialogue itself is a positive sign."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Indian negotiating team held talks with the
hijackers till 0200 hours this morning. "But it came to a
situation of impasse. There were some apprehension about no
further resumption of negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts were made thereafter to resume the dialogue which was
done, he said, " the negotiations are now extremely delicately
poised."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee Thursday night
called on President K. R. Narayanan and apprised him of the latest
developments in the hijacking crisis.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that Vajpayee briefed the president on
the crisis since the hijacking took place on December 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
