<HEADLINE> Feature: "Without Peace, We Will Have Nothing!"  By Zhang Ruiling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia December 30 (Xinhua) -- "Without peace, We
will have nothing, let alone the Angkor festival", that is the
common aspiration expressed by many Cambodian people these days in
celebrate the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
"We are truly happy to see that the peace appear in every
corner of our country which we have waited for a long time. The
present situation allows us to celebrate together the great
extravaganza with joy and confidence," a young man told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"We wish our country has a everlasting peace, no fighting and
war from now on," added a young women.
</P>
<P>
It is the first grand festival that Cambodia held in Angkor Wat
and under such a peaceful circumstances in more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Nearly three decades of civil war and lingering unrest have
turned Cambodia into not only the one of most heavily mined
countries in the world, but also the one of poorest countries in
the world.
</P>
<P>
"The unrest made us living in horror and fear, dare not to go
out in the night or enjoy ourselves in many public places," a
businessman said. "Now the security in the whole country changed
greatly. People can go everywhere to enjoy the millennium ceremony,
" he added.
</P>
<P>
At the time when the old millennium ends and the new millennium
begins, Cambodia's new coalition government, set up in late 1999,
has succeeded in the application of the policy of national
reconciliation under the wise leadership of King Norodom Sihanouk.
The peace, political stability and social security have returned
to the country.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Festival Angkor-2000, starts from Thursday, are
expected to attract more than 100,000 people, most of them are
Cambodians from all over the country, even the remotest provinces -
- Ratanakiri, Mondolkiri and Stung Treng.
</P>
<P>
"Though I am a Cambodian, I have never seen the Angkor Temples
before due to the turmoil in the country. Now we have peace, so I
and my family traveled long distance to take part in the
celebration here," an old man from Kompong Thum province told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very exciting, because I have fulfilled my wish today. I
saw the Angkor Temples, the great symbol of our country and the
incomparable construction achieved by our ancestors," a Buddhist
monk from Takeo province said.
</P>
<P>
The National Route 6 to Siem Reap, the location of Angkor Wat,
are crowed with people, cars, trucks and other means of
transportation these days.
</P>
<P>
Many preparations have been done by the government and the
related sectors in an effort to let the people enjoying the
festival. The main road leading to Siem Reap has been repaired and
upgraded. More street lights were installed along a road from the
airport direct to the temple complex. It also has deployed
additional police for security.
</P>
<P>
The celebration, which are held simultaneously in Bayon Temple
and Siem Reap Sport Stadium as well as other provinces, will run
from December 30, 1999, to January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Senate President Chea Sim, President of the National Assembly
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, Prime Minister Hun Sen and other senior
officials are at the present and will deliver the speeches. Also
at present are some diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The celebration will feature the traditional dances, modern
music, fireworks display and the sound of drums. And 2,000
Buddhist monks will offer blessing when the old millennium ends
and the new one begins.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 500 traditional hot air balloons will be
launched at midnight on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
The national TV station, TVK will directly beam the three-day
Angkor festival to 126 countries.
</P>
<P>
"We are not claiming that our festival will be international
standards. The important thing is we are doing our best to promote
peace, culture and tourism," Tourism Minister Veng Sereyvuth said.
</P>
</TEXT>
