<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Arabs, Israelis Forge Ahead Toward Comprehensive Peace by Tan Xinmu, Qi Deliang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- With the revival of peace
talks on both Palestinian and Syrian tracks in 1999, the Middle
East peace process is gaining momentum toward an overall settlement
between Israel and the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Ending a three-year deadlock, peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinians on interim affairs resumed in July, two months after
Labor party leader Ehud Barak defeated then hardline Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu in the general elections.
</P>
<P>
In early September, Israel and the Palestinians signed Sharm el
Sheikh memorandum on implementation of what Tel Aviv had committed
to in the Wye agreement a year before.
</P>
<P>
The most significant of the latest deal was an exact timetable
for the two sides to reach a permanent peace accord. They are to
produce a framework deal next February and complete a detailed
peace treaty next September.
</P>
<P>
The process of negotiating the Sharm el Sheikh memo also helped
restore the shattered mutual confidence between the two sides - the
Palestinians went to the negotiating table with reluctance and
suspicion, but eventually got a better deal than the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
So far, the memo has been carried out in earnest by and large,
although not without hindrances and frustrations.
</P>
<P>
Israel has handed over 7 percent of the West Bank to the
Palestinians in the first stage of redeployments, released 350
Palestinian political prisoners, and opened a safe passage route
linking the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Their final-status talks on resolving the thorniest issues such
as Palestinian statehood, fate of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements and
Palestinian refugees, kicked off on September 13.
</P>
<P>
Although there were only 100 days left to finish a framework
deal on ending the decade-old conflicts, the two sides expressed
confidence that they can meet the target date.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of Israeli-Syrian talks, however, came somewhat
as a surprise. After Barak took office, the two sides exchanged
words of peace; but the lack of confidence and a clear formula
prevented the negotiations from being reopened at an early stage.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that there were at least three factors leading
to the resumption of the Israeli-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The first was that Syrian President Hafez al-Assad reached
better understanding of Barak's intention to achieve peace. After
several months of careful observation, Assad believed that Barak
was sincere in his pursuit of a comprehensive peace, and that the
current favorable opportunity should not be missed again as in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The second was that U.S. President Bill Clinton was eager to
secure a major diplomatic achievement before his second term ends
in early 2001. It was revealed that Washington had conducted
intensive quiet diplomacy between the two sides in the last several
months and Clinton had been personally involved by talking to Barak
and Assad on the phone frequently.
</P>
<P>
The third factor was that Barak pledged to withdraw Israeli
troops out of south Lebanon by July next year, even without
security arrangements with Beirut.
</P>
<P>
A potential unilateral Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon would
undoubtedly strip Damascus of an important card it wants to
leverage Israel for more concessions on the Golan Heights, a
strategic plateau Israel seized from Syria in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have been upbeat about the renewed negotiations,
saying a peace deal could be within reach in week or in months, for
about 80 percent of their disputes have been resolved.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, where Syria has been a major power-broker, would join
in negotiations soon with Israel on Israeli troop withdrawal from
its south. Israel carved out a border strip there in 1985 as a
declared aim of protecting its north from cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The progress on all the tracks of Middle East peace-making is an
immediate result of Barak's new policies.
</P>
<P>
Barak has claimed that no one understands better than he the
vital importance of security for Israel. Unlike Netanyahu, who used
security as an excuse for his hardline policies, Barak realizes
that the best way to achieve security is through peace.
</P>
<P>
He has reiterated his promise to end the decade-old conflict
between the Jewish people and its Arab neighbors. He also expressed
readiness to make "painful concessions" in order to achieve this
goal.
</P>
<P>
Judging from a broader perspective, the Middle East peace
process has moved forward due to persistent Arab struggle and
international efforts. The Israelis, on the other hand, have been
tired of living in tension, clashes and international isolation.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East has never been so close to a comprehensive
peace, whose realization, however, is not a done deal. There are
still at least three main challenges to be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the pressure of time. The time frame for agreements on
all the tracks is tight, but the issues are the most difficult ones
- on the Palestinian track, wide gaps remain on almost every final-
status issue with no quick solutions in sight.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Israel has proposed a two-step mechanism for
realizing permanent peace - resolving less difficult issues first
and then the most tough ones, such as the fate of Jerusalem and
Palestinian refugees,
</P>
<P>
Barak said a few months ago that if the two sides failed to
agree on an outline by February, they might have to forgo a final
accord and instead negotiate long-term interim agreements on most
issues.
</P>
<P>
On the Syrian track, the two sides restarted the talks "from the
point where they left off," but the question of what the point was
is still open to different interpretations.
</P>
<P>
Syria insists that talks resume from what it says was a verbal
promise by the late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin to hand
back all the Golan in exchange for peace and security measures. But
Israel has denied the existence of such a promise.
</P>
<P>
In their two days of talks held in Washington on December 15 and
December 16, Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa
only agreed on how the negotiations should proceed. Substantial
discussions have not yet started.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, Barak faces a tremendous task of selling any of his
agreements to the Israeli public, for he has promised to subject
any deal to a national referendum.
</P>
<P>
This idea not only restricts his flexibility in negotiations,
but also imposes on him a lot of persuasion work to garner a
majority of public support.
</P>
<P>
Although most Israelis support the peace process, they differ on
how peace can be achieved. It might be easier for them to accept a
demilitarized Palestinian state than a partitioned city of
Jerusalem. a larger troop withdrawal from the West Bank for the
Palestinians than a return of the Golan to Syria.
</P>
<P>
To ensure wide support for his peace policies, Barak formed a
coalition government that has the widest parliamentary majority in
decades. But rift set in over the resumption of talks with Syrian.
</P>
<P>
Barak went to Washington for talks with Sharaa backed with only
a narrow parliamentary majority, as some coalition partners voted
against or abstained.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, terrorism poses as serious a threat to the peace
process as before.
</P>
<P>
Extremists opposed to peace-making between Israel and the Arabs
will keep attempting to derail the peace process. Since the signing
of the Sharm el Sheikh deal, there have been several terror attacks
inside Israel, and increased terrorist activities are predicted as
the peace process proceeds.
</P>
<P>
Like his mentor Rabin, Barak has kept the peace process running
in face of terror attacks in order not to play into the hands of
terrorists. But there is still risk of the peace process being
derailed if terror attacks inflict serious fatalities. The Israeli-
Syrian talks came to a halt in early 1996 mainly because of a
string of suicide bombings inside Israel.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, with a shared desire and determination to avert
further conflicts and wars, the Israelis and the Arabs are believed
to overcome all the difficulties to usher the Middle East into a
new millenium of comprehensive and lasting peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
