<HEADLINE> Turkey Well-prepared for Y2K in All Sectors: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said on Friday that the country has taken measures against
the Y2K problem in all sectors from transportation to communication
and energy.
</P>
<P>
The primer warned, however, that people should be careful when
using computer-operated systems such as elevators around midnight,
the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that the Prime Ministry prepared a Y2K National
Action Plan to minimize the negative effects of the problem and to
prevent interruptions in basic services.
</P>
<P>
Under a National Contingency Plan, forwarded by the Turkish
Prime Ministry Crisis Management Center which has kept contact with
other
countries, authorities from all related institutions will be on
duties in the center from December 31, 1999 to January 3, 2000 in
case possible computer problems related to Y2K occur.
</P>
<P>
Trains in subways will not operate between 11:45 p.m. (2145 GMT)
on Friday and 00:15 (1015 GMT) a.m. on Saturday while Istanbul
strait will be closed to marine traffic between 6 p.m. (1600 GMT)
on Friday and 6 a.m. (0400 GMT) on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about precautions taken in finance, Ecevit said that
banks had kept hard copies or used other methods to save
information in their computers, assuring people that they should
not worry about their saving deposits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
