<HEADLINE> Clerides Wishes Way Open up for Cyprus Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides Friday evening expressed the wish "the way will open up in
the year 2000 for a just, viable and workable solution" to the
Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
In his New Year message, the president also wished "the
unhindered continuation of Cyprus' accession course to the European
Union (EU)."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974. Efforts
have been made to reunite the island through a bizonal, bicommunal
federation formula, so far produced no tangible results.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus started substantive accession talks with the EU in
November 1998 and hopes to be admitted by January 2003.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the strategy followed on both these issues "has
set in motion various forces which can make a decisive contribution
to a solution."
</P>
<P>
He added, however, that "in order to attain our goals we need to
achieve the greatest possible unity in our internal front, as well
as to continue our excellent cooperation with the Greek
government."
</P>
<P>
Clerides stressed "we have the required capabilities and for
this reason we have to devote all our energy to turn into reality
in the first years of the new millennium our common vision for a
new Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
He said "tonight not only pleasant but also unpleasant memories
come to our mind more vividly. One of these, which continues to be
a painful reality, is the continuing occupation of about one third
of our homeland by Turkey, with all its repercussions which still
affect us."
</P>
<P>
"I am certain however, that this painful memory strengthens our
endurance and determination to struggle and keep our optimism and
hope alive and that, finally, justice will be restored in our long-
suffering country to the benefits of all Cypriots," Clerides added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
