<HEADLINE> AL Chief Calls for Iraqi Steps to Heal Arab Rifts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid on Friday urged Iraq to take creative
steps in a bid to help heal the rifts in the Arab world in the
coming new era.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued hours before the advent of the third
millennium, Abdel-Meguid spoke of the major events that occurred in
the Arab world this century and the 22-nation pan-Arab forum's
expectations and hopes.
</P>
<P>
He singled out one momentous event in the last decade: Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait on August 2, 1990, which, he regretted, had a
clear negative impact on Arab solidarity and incised a deep wound
in inter-Arab relations still felt till now.
</P>
<P>
Such rifts should be remedied through creative overtures and
well-calculated concessions by Iraq, the AL chief said.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid called on Iraq to honor the relevant United Nations
Security Council resolutions, a move which he said would greatly
contribute to restoring Arab unity and clearing Arab atmospheres.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait prompted the U.N. Security Council to
imposed crippling economic sanctions on it. The sanctions will not
be lifted until Iraq complies with the resolutions demanding, among
other things, elimination of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kuwait and some other Gulf Arab countries have not
forgiven Baghdad due to its failure to officially apologize for the
invasion.
</P>
<P>
Asserting the importance of intensifying cooperation between the
Arab League and the other regional and international organizations,
Abdel-Meguid expressed keenness on developing the values of dialog
and understanding among world societies and renunciation of
violence and extremism.
</P>
<P>
On the threshold of the third millennium, the AL cherishes the
hope for stronger international cooperation and efforts in securing
world peace and stability, and achieving sustained development, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Arab countries to promote inter-Arab trade and
economic cooperation, and make joint efforts to set up the aspired
Arab common market for the benefit of the Arab nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
