<HEADLINE> Italian Premier Sends Message to Putin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema
sent his best wishes to the Russian interim president, Premier
Vladimir Putin, appointed Friday after the shock resignation of
his mentor Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema expressed his and the Italian government's best wishes
for a "full and fruitful performance of your high mission."
</P>
<P>
"I trust that the friendship between our two countries may help
strengthen the conditions of peace and stability in Europe," D'
Alema said, voicing the hope for a swift solution to the Chechnya
conflict, "respecting human rights and ending the suffering of the
civilian population."
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said he thought "excellent" bilateral ties could be
further reinforced, also via the Italian-Russian partnership
accord.
</P>
<P>
"I am certain that under your guidance, in this transitional
phase also, the Russian Federation will continue its policy of
consolidating democracy, economic reforms and international
collaboration," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I unite with these sentiments the best wishes for peace and
prosperity for our friend the Russian people, and personal well-
being for yourself and your family," he said.
</P>
<P>
"With my highest regards and in the hope that I may be able to
meet you shortly," D'Alema said in conclusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
