<HEADLINE> S. African Deputy President Calls for National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Jacob Zuma said Friday that his country will give
priority to achieving unity in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Zuma, however, admitted that the achievement of unity poses a
main challenge to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Of highest priority is... driving the consistent
transformation of South Africa into a non-racial, non-sexist
society -- in short, the molding of a united nation," he told
revelers gathering at the Union Building in Pretoria to celebrate
the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
He said the creation of a single nation depended on bridging
the gulf between rich and poor, white and black.
</P>
<P>
This would require a renewed focus on ending poverty, hunger,
insecurity and illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
This transformative process requires great efforts to create an
ever expanding floor of opportunities for all South Africans, Zuma
said.
</P>
<P>
South Africans should recognize that their fellow citizens
were at root simple, uncomplicated human beings -- a realization
which should help to bind the nation as it strides into the new
millennium, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zuma was the main speaker at Pretoria's official 6 million rand
(1 million U.S. dollar) millennium bash, expected to be attended
by up to 15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
He said putting the government's reconstruction and development
program into effect would demand the same degree of dedication,
skill and courage as the struggle for democracy.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said South Africa was standing at the threshold of a new
epoch and that the country had the potential of becoming the
economic engine room of the entire continent.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the future of the continent, he said political
stability and peace were indispensable ingredients for Africa's
revival.
</P>
<P>
It would also require the creation of a shared sense of purpose
among Africans, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The continent must recapture the numerous opportunities it has
lost because of misguided policies," Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
"As we mark the festive season, let the message of peace and
goodwill towards our fellow human beings ring out throughout the
land," Zuma said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
