<HEADLINE> Mandela Urges Greater Efforts to Fight World's Current Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela said Friday that greater efforts should
be made to deal with the world's current woes in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
In his millennium message broadcast by the South African
Broadcasting Corporation, Mandela reminded the public that despite
advances made in the 20th century, many among the world's
population still live in abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
The world closed the century with most people still languishing
in poverty, subjected to hunger, preventable disease, illiteracy
and insufficient shelter, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have been fortunate to live through most of the century. It
brought such great hope and at other times such disappointment,"
Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
"In some ways we outstreaked the achievements of our ancestors
over all the preceding centuries," he said. "In other ways we fell
short of what we hoped for and what was indeed possible."
</P>
<P>
"We lived through two world wars and many more localized
conflicts and we also witnessed the establishment of the U.N. and
other multilateral bodies for the peaceful resolution of conflicts,
" he added.
</P>
<P>
Humanity should take advantage of the advances in science and
technology, industry and learning to address the needs of the
world's population, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
