<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: 1999, Year of Rekindled Hope for Nigeria (by Song Li) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The year 1999 is a year of
rekindled hope for Nigerians. After a decade and half of military
misrule, which made Nigeria plummet from a middle-income country
to one of the world's poorest, Nigerian people chose Olusegun
Obasanjo and his civilian government to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo took over on May 29 from the military's hand a country
on the edge of collapse. When he pledged political stability, good
governance and economic recovery in his inauguration address, some
foreign journalists simply thought "he stopped short of promising
miracles."
</P>
<P>
Miracles can't come in a short period of seven months. Yet,
remarkable signs of improvement do appear on Obasanjo's cause of
"making Nigeria great again."
</P>
<P>
In the past seven months, the top priority for Obasanjo is to
make the civilian government to root in Nigeria, a country ruled
by the military in 28 years out of its 39-year history after
independence.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo started his work by purging the military. In half a
month following his inauguration, more than 100 generals lost
their jobs and retired on a voluntary or compulsory basis.
</P>
<P>
Through staffing the high-ranking positions of the armed forces
by younger generations of officers, Obasanjo, who is also a
retired general, took full control of the county's restive
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
To achieve political stability, Obasanjo paid special attention
to keep a balance in appointing government officials. His cabinet
posts were evenly distributed among the country's nearly 40
states, and three big ethnic groups, the Yoruba, Hausa, and Igbo.
</P>
<P>
To win the people's support, he put anti-corruption at the
center of his policy.
</P>
<P>
Corruption is a hallmark character of Nigeria on the world
stage. If the country remained to be in this image, no foreign
investment would start to flow into this country, said Obasanjo
repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
Corruption also fueled the country's political instability,
for it was placing a high premium on the control of state office.
Some estimated about 40 billion U.S. dollars of public treasure
has been looted out and stacked in foreign banks by corrupt
officials under the past military regimes.
</P>
<P>
In the past months, hundreds of millions of these ill-gotten
assets have been taken back. Under the request of the Nigerian
government, Swiss froze in November bank accounts worth billions
of dollars under the name of former military dictator Sani Abacha
and his associates.
</P>
<P>
The new government also ordered to freeze and re-examine
contracts signed by former military regimes, including his own. In
a quite unusual stance, the first bill Obasanjo sent to the
National Assembly, the country's top legislature, is an anti-
corruption act, which may sentence corrupt officials for as long
as seven years in jail if it were passed into law. Long neglected
utility industries such as petroleum, electricity and water
supplies resumed normal functioning within months of Obasanjo's
coming into power. The quickly devaluating naira stabilized at a
level of 100 naira to one U.S. dollar. These have won acclamation
from the average Nigerians. Privatization and diversity of its
economy are two main thrusts of his economic policy. The long
delayed multi-billion dollar liquefied natural gas plant started
supplying gas to Europe in November. The West African natural gas
pipeline project is also underway. Obasanjo pays particular
attention to the development of agriculture by providing favorite
loans to the farmers. He also encourages the growth of small and
medium-sized enterprises in a bid to boost the employment
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Stressing its ties with the West and leadership in Africa are
the two pillars of Obasanjo's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
With the dawning of democracy in this country, Western
countries resumed full ties with Nigeria. Western dignities
including French President Jacques Chirac, Canadian President Jean
Chretien and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright visited
Nigeria. In a quite unusual stance, Obasanjo paid three visits to
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria hopes to count on the West's help in the areas of debt
alleviation, privatization, and investment. It also hopes the
United States and other Western countries can stand out to
intervene in case there were a coup in the future.
</P>
<P>
For Nigeria in 1999, there was a mixed picture of withdrawal
form certain regional commitments for economic considerations and
demonstrated desires to exert shared leadership with South Africa
in the South Sahara African continent.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria successfully helped to ink the Lome peace accord this
July ending the decade-long civil war in Sierra Leone, and the
latter shifted its commitment to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria also helped to pacify the hostility between Liberia and
Guinea, and set up a mediation and security mechanism within the
frame work the Economic Community of West Africa States (ECOWAS)
at the 22nd ECOWAS summit held in November in Togo's capital Lome.
</P>
<P>
Despite the achievements, which may justifiably bring Nigerians
optimism at the threshold of a new millennium. Daunting challenges
still remain for Obasanjo to finish the rest of his four year term.
</P>
<P>
Debt alleviation and ethnic conflicts, among others, are among
the most urgent and grim ones.
</P>
<P>
With an external debt of about 29 billion dollars, Nigeria is
Africa's largest debtor nation. To fully service debt obligations,
Nigeria has to pay 4 billion dollars, almost 80 percent of the
federal budget in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Debt alleviation was often the dominating topic in Nigerian
leaders' trips to the U.S. and European countries or their talks
with the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Despite the efforts, the main Western countries only agreed to
a re-scheduling instead of a straight cancellation of the country'
s debts. In the years to come, the debt problem is sure to be the
key to Nigeria's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's history since its independence is dominated by
competition for power and resources between the three main ethnic
groups -- the Hausa-Fulani in the north, the Yoruba in the
southwest and Igbo in the southeast. Obasanjo has been ruling on a
delicate balance of power between the three, though with
unavoidable consequences of inner fighting and low administrative
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Members of the National Assembly, who are divided more by
geographical definition than political differences, actually have
done nothing except quarreling with each other since their
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic conflicts in the oil producing Niger delta region are
also growing more and more violent. Several hundred people were
killed in an ethnic clash triggered only a day after Obasanjo's
stepping into power. A dozen of federal policemen were recently
murdered by militant Ijaw youths in Beyalsa on the delta. In the
north, Zamfara State in December announced its adoption of the
Islamic Sharia as a state law, which triggered protests from the
Christian south.
</P>
<P>
All this, if improperly handled, could still endanger the
hardly earned stability in Africa's most populous country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin Talk on Phone After Yeltsin's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two leaders spoke for about 20 minutes. Clinton saluted
Russia's movement to democracy under Yeltsin and pledged to work
with the Russian people, Acting President Vladimir Putin, the
winner of next year's presidential election, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
"He (Yeltsin) said that Russians will remain committed to their
constitution, democracy, arms control, (and) market economics. He
made a strong case for President Putin as a strong, intelligent
and capable man," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told Yeltsin historians will regard him as "someone who
guided Russia to the point of democracy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States had no advance notice of Yeltsin's
resignation, announced earlier Friday, Lockhart said. Another
White House spokesman said earlier that the resignation was
dramatic, but not a complete surprise.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart added that the alert status of the U.S. military had
not changed. Top military officers from both countries currently
were working closely together in Colorado, monitoring any
potential computer problems related to the changeover to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, Clinton said in a statement that he would work
with the Russian leader "together to advance common interests"
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We have had our differences, such as on Chechnya, but
President Yeltsin and my starting point has always been how Russia
and the United States could work together to advance common
interests," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He indicated, however, that the U.S.-Russian relationship had
achieved "genuine progress." About 5,000 long-range strategic
nuclear weapons had been dismantled in the U.S. and Russia, and
the two country worked together to keep peace on the Balkans,
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"In this spirit, I look forward to working with Acting
President Putin as the Russian people begin this process of making
the transition from one democratically elected president to the
other," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
