<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: War Dominates S.Lanka's Elections By Lian Guohui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- For Sri Lankans, the passing
1999 is a politically important year dominated by provincial
elections and the presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
However, the central issue in all the elections is war and
peace.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by the seemingly unending ethnic
conflicts since 1983 between government troops and the separatist
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels who demand a
separate state for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east.
</P>
<P>
For President Chandrika Kumaratunga, the success or failure in
her political career hinges on the resolution of the bloody ethnic
war.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Kumaratunga was voted to power in November 1994 with a
landslide 62 percent majority, partly because of her pledge to
bring peace back to the war-torn island country.
</P>
<P>
But a few months after her victory, peace talks between the
government and the LTTE broke down and hostilities resumed.
</P>
<P>
Since then Kumaratunga followed a war-for-peace solution to the
ethnic problem.
</P>
<P>
By October 1999, government troops have succeeded in reducing
the amount of rebel territory from 9,100 square kms in 1994 to 3,
200 square kms.
</P>
<P>
The biggest military victory was the recapture of the northern
Jaffna peninsula in 1996 where the LTTE had established their de
facto state for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
On the political front, Kumaratunga initiated a devolution
package to give more power to local administrations, including one
dominated by ethnic Tamils.
</P>
<P>
However, both measures have failed to produce decisive effects
so far to end the ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
A string of military defeats in the northern Wanni region early
last month stripped the government of a vast area that had taken
the army more than two years to capture. Meanwhile, the devolution
package has yet to gain the necessary two-thirds majority in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
With only one year left of the current term, hope is slim for
Mrs.Kumaratunga to break the stalemate on the ethnic problem from
both military and political aspects.
</P>
<P>
People's disappointment with the government is much obvious as
the president has failed to fulfill her promise to bring back
peace in her last election campaign.
</P>
<P>
The staggering war expenditure has slowed down the country's
economic development as well.
</P>
<P>
According to Sri Lanka's Central Bank, its Gross Domestic
Product (GDP growth rate has dropped from 6.3 percent in 1997 to 4.
7 percent in 1998, and is expected to drop further this year to
four percent.
</P>
<P>
With her political career in jeopardy, Chandrika Kumaratunga on
October 20 called the presidential elections nearly a year ahead
of the scheduled date of next November.
</P>
<P>
The move was intended to catch the opposition United National
Party (UNP) in surprise. Meanwhile, it can take advantage of the
ruling People's Alliance (PA)'s victory in the seven provincial
councils elections held in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Kumaratunga launched a massive election campaign
for the country's fourth presidential election on December 21,
fully utilizing the powerful state propaganda machinery.
</P>
<P>
But people will choose the one who gives them the best hope of
ending this protracted ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga's main rival, UNP leader Ranil Wickremesinghe tried
to woo voters by his pledge to solve the ethnic problem with
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
He said once elected, he would open talks with the LTTE and
establish an interim council in the Tamil-dominated northeast.
</P>
<P>
He also planned to create a conducive atmosphere by sending
food and medicine to regions held by the LTTE, lift military
restrictions on fishing and farming and stop the harassment of
Tamil civilians.
</P>
<P>
Wickremesinghe's promise seemed not only comply with people's
war-weariness, but also got the favor of the LTTE rebels, who
would rather cooperate with a mild peace advocator than an
aggressive war supporter.
</P>
<P>
Analysts had expected a neck and neck race between Kumaratunga
and Wickremesinghe until December 18 when twin bombings occurred
in and near Colombo at the last election rallies of the PA and UNP.
</P>
<P>
The bombings, which was blamed on the LTTE, had killed 35
people and injured 129 others including the president herself and
three cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Kumaratunga, who probably lost her right eye in the
assassination attempt, was believed to have obtained more sympathy
votes from the majority Sinhalese voters.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga was reelected in the end with a narrow majority of
51.12 percent, while Wickremesinghe obtained 42.71 percent.
</P>
<P>
The next crucial step for the president to take is call for
early parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
The mood of utmost confidence among government leaders and
within the ruling alliance after the election, plus the trend of
defection of UNP parliament members to the ruling party would
undoubtedly enable Mrs. Kumaratunga to get the two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
But for ordinary people, whoever ends the war, who scores the
last victory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
