<HEADLINE> (Updated) Yeltsin Resignation Prompts Mix Reaction in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 31 (Xinhua) -- President Boris Yeltsin's
announcement Friday to step down and name Prime Minister Vladimir
Putin as acting president prompted mixed reactions across the
Russian political arena.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Chubais, a former senior aide to Yeltsin, said the move
was a "stroke of genius."
</P>
<P>
"It was the perfect decision, courageous and profound," he said,
adding that many politicians would come to realize Yeltsin's
importance in the wake of the resignation.
</P>
<P>
However, Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the Russian Communist
Party, said Yeltsin's stepping down six months before the
expiration of his term was a result of a 10-year struggle with
Russia's patriots and Communists, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"Yeltsin's party of power has fallen... the people's
impeachment of Yeltsin has taken place," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's resignation was widely seen as a move that would
further boost Prime Minister Vladimir Putin's chances of winning
the next presidential elections, now moved to March.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov called on all healthy forces to be mobilized "to ward
off the coming to power of another version of an anti-popular
regime."
</P>
<P>
Boris Berezovsky, a prominent business tycoon widely known for
his political connections, praised Yeltsin's move as a right
decision.
</P>
<P>
"Yeltsin once again proved to everybody that he is the right
choice for Russia, a powerful, great and unpredictable country for
everyone but us, those who were born, live and will die here,"
Interfax quoted Berezovsky as saying.
</P>
<P>
Boris Nemtsov, a former Yeltsin aide who now heads the Union of
Right-Wing Forces, said Yeltsin's resignation gave Putin a real
chance to become the future Russian president.
</P>
<P>
"Yeltsin has left as impressively as he came. This was done not
only impressively but also with fine timing: after the
parliamentary elections and before the New Year," Nemtsov said.
</P>
<P>
Former Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin expressed the belief
that Putin would be victorious in the upcoming presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
"There are three months until the elections and I do not see
any serious opponents to Putin," Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Yeltsin's move was taken in
the interests of the Russian state to ensure that the new
generation of Russian politicians who have won a good reputation
might continue working for the benefit of Russia with redoubled
strength."
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Sergeyev described Yeltsin's resignation as "
an event of enormous importance," adding that he understood "the
emotions which filled Yeltsin."
</P>
<P>
He praised Yeltsin's intellect behind the resignation. "Many
will soon understand the important role of Boris Yeltsin in
Russian history," he said.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo said Yeltsin's presidency
had marked a whole epoch in the history of the Russian state.
</P>
</TEXT>
