<HEADLINE> Japan Announces Ready For Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- As the year 2000 is approaching,
Japan Friday declared itself ready for the Y2K bug, launching a
task force headed by Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi to gather
information about problems related to the computer problem.
</P>
<P>
The task force, launched at the prime minister's official
residence at 6 p.m. (local time), will obtain information about
computer problems in New Zealand through the Japanese embassy
there as New Zealand is the first industrialized nation to greet
the new year.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi is expected to announce details of problems arising from
the millennium bug at 0:50 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"It is essential that we gather information as quickly as
possible to ensure that the people are informed," Japanese Chief
Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki said when announcing the launch of
the Y2K task force.
</P>
<P>
"Should anything happen, we must take steps to ensure that
people's lives are not affected," the top government spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than two million people in the country's public
and private sectors went on alert to prepare for the millennium
bug.
</P>
<P>
They include 806,000 fire fighters, 106,000 police officers, 96,
000 members of the Self-Defense Forces and 2,000 civil servants
from government ministries and agencies.
</P>
<P>
Some 270,000 workers in the banking, brokerage and insurance
industries will also be on duty during the New Year season to
prepare for any computer breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
With jitters over possible blackouts from the millennium bug,
Japan's electric power companies had some 16,000 workers on
standby, while railway companies plan to halt all train services
for about five minutes around midday Friday to check for problems
in signals and other equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
