<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Says Resignation of Yeltsin "Constitutional" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin said that the surprise announcement by Russian President
Boris Yeltsin to resign "conforms to the constitutional rules
existing in Russia."
</P>
<P>
"I can only say at this moment that the decision of resignation
of President Yeltsin, and of the nomination as acting president of
Prime Minister Putin and the fixing of the date of the
presidential elections are in conformity to the existing
constitutional rules in Russia," Agence France-Presse quoted
Jospin as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia from now on is opening a period of election
and "it is the game of democracy which will express itself."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Gaullist Rally for the Republic (RPR) said that
Yeltsin's resignation would put an end to "a long period of
uncertainty" in Russia.
</P>
<P>
The RPR said in a statement that it hopes that "the step which
is beginning will open for the Russian people an era of
reinforcement of democracy, indispensable economic readjustment
and stability."
</P>
<P>
"France, as well as Europe, will have a role to play for
supporting all the efforts which could be made in this direction
by the new political leaders of this great country who will be
elected next March during the early presidential election, said
the statement. 
</P>
