<HEADLINE> South African President Delivers New Millennium Message </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Thabo Mbeki Friday delivered a new millennium message, urging all
Africans to take a stand against war, poverty and corruption and
make the next century an era of good hope.
</P>
<P>
In a new year message to be broadcast on television and radio
late Friday, Mbeki said all Africans could be proud of the ending
of colonialism on their continent.
</P>
<P>
However, he said they had not "taken advantage of the fact of
our liberation to address the fundamental interests of our peoples
" due to too many military coups and too many wars within and
between countries on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki pointed out that the approaching century "will and must
be a century of hope". He called on all African people, including
South Africans, to do everything they could to boost
reconciliation among people, wipe out the legacy of racism, sexism
and discrimination against disabled people, and fight against
crime and poverty.
</P>
<P>
South Africans should also strive for common social progress
with all their neighbors and all people of the continent in
pursuit of the "noble goal" of an African renaissance, he said.
</P>
