<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Regrets Yeltsin's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi said Friday he regretted Russian President Boris Yeltsin's
resignation, but added he hoped to work with Yeltsin's successor
to achieve the goal of concluding a peace treaty between the two
countries by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
"I am sorry that President Yeltsin decided to resign, and I
would like to offer my heartfelt praise toward his achievements,"
Obuchi said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"I hope to cooperate with Russia's new leader to further
promote (the trend) of developing bilateral relations in various
fields ... and to do our utmost to conclude a peace treaty by 2000
" based on the previous agreements, he added.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Russia have not concluded a peace treaty due to a
long-standing territorial dispute over Russia-held islands off
Japan's main northern island of Hokkaido. The two countries had
been working to realize a visit to Tokyo by Yeltsin in spring for
talks on the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin announced earlier in the day that he is resigning and
appointed Prime Minister Vladimir Putin as acting president.
</P>
