<HEADLINE> Philippine 'Millennium Baby' to Reap Scholarship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The first infant to be born
through normal delivery in a Philippine government-accredited
hospital after the clock strikes 12:00 Friday night will be dubbed
the "Millennium Baby" and awarded with a college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Edgardo Angara of the Department of Agriculture, who
also heads the Presidential Commission on the New Century and the
Millennium (PCNCM), said Friday the scholarship grant will ensure
the Millennium Baby's bright future through education.
</P>
<P>
Angara said in a radio interview that the Millennium Baby will
also get an array of gift packages as part of the activities to
mark the coming of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The Millennium Baby scholarship grant is part of the activities
of the week-long millennium celebrations that started on December
26 throughout the country to welcome the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
According to the project's sponsor, a baby-care magazine, the
Millennium Baby "serves as a rallying symbol to renew our society'
s commitment to the future of the next generation of Filipinos."
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada created the PCNCM on July
23 this year to oversee the country's celebration of the new
millennium as well as the adoption of policies and programs
related to agriculture and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The PCNCM was also tasked to prepare and recommend to the
president the Master Plan on the Millennium and the New Century,
with emphasis on science and technology to advance the country's
agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
Estrada and government officials join in welcoming the new
millennium at the Rizal Park in Manila Friday night. They will
lead the Kapit-Bisig (linking of arms) ritual at the park to
symbolize unity among Filipinos, as the nation counts down the few
remaining seconds of the old millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
