<HEADLINE> Hijackers, Militants to Leave Afghanistan  Soon-Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- All the five hijackers of an
Indian airliner and three Muslim militants released by the Indian
government will leave Afghanistan in 10 hours, the Taliban's
foreign minister said Friday, according to Taliban sources here.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban authorities would not grant political asylum to any
of them, he said.
</P>
<P>
The eight-day hijacking drama ended after an agreement was
reached between the Indian government and the hijackers on the
release of the hostages in exchange for three jailed Muslim
militants.
</P>
<P>
The five hijackers were seen to have left the plane, which had
been stranded at the Kandahar airport in Afghanistan over the past
week with more than 150 passengers and crew on board, sources from
Kandahar said.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Coordinator for Afghanistan Eric de Mul, who has
been involved in the negotiations, confirmed that under the
agreement ending the hijacking all three prisoners released by
India and the five hijackers had been handed to the Taliban
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The three militants had arrived in Kandahar earlier Friday
along with Indian Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh. 
</P>
