<HEADLINE> 2nd Lead: Passengers of Hijacked Jet Leave For Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Passengers of the hijacked
Indian jet Have left for home Friday evening from Kandhar aboard a
special Indian plane, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The eight-day ordeal of the 155 passengers and crew of the
hijacked Indian plane came to a dramatic end minutes after the
External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh landed at Kandahar airport
in southern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The passengers, held hostage for eight days by six Islamic hard-
liners aboard an Indian Airlines Airbus A-300, were released
following a talk between Jaswant Singh and the hijackers earlier
today.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said a decision had been made on the
future of the hijackers during the talk.
</P>
<P>
"A decision has been reached on what will happen to them (
hijackers) and the Taliban would announce it shortly, United
Nations coordinator for Afghanistan Erick de Mul reportedly said
after the hijackers drove away from Kandahar airport with three
militants, released by India.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) defended the government
decision to free the three hard-core militants in return for the
release of hostages on board the Indian Airlines plane, hijacked
last Friday on its from Kathmandu to New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
BJP vice president J. P. Mathur said here shortly after the
solution of the hostage crisis that the image of India as a sober,
reliable country "has been enhanced in the world and the
international community should realize the growing danger of
Islamic fundamentalism."
</P>
<P>
Two special aircraft with carrying External Affairs Minister
Jaswant Singh and the three hard-core militants aboard reached
Kandahar at 1640 hours local time, reports reaching here said.
</P>
</TEXT>
