<P>
NEW DELHI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee Friday night defended the release of three
militants in exchange for 155 passengers, hold as hostages aboard
a hijacked Indian plane.
</P>
<P>
In his new year message broadcast over the official Doordarshan
television, Vajpayee said his government was able to "
substantially scale down" the demand" of the hijackers.
</P>
<P>
"The hijackers had demanded the release of 36 terrorists. We
were able to substantially scale down their demand," Vajpayee said,
adding that India's first resolution for the new century would be
to join hands across the country to rid the world of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In dealing with the hijackers, the prime minister said, the
government was guided by two concerns: the safety of the
passengers and the crew, and the long-term, overall interests of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Stating that the hijacking, "diabolic and evil as it is", is
but the latest manifestation of terrorism, Vajpayee said "India
shall not spare any effort to thwart the phenomenon of terrorism
itself."
</P>
<P>
Describing terrorism as "crime against humanity", he said time
had come for the world to "confront this evil, to act in concert
and crush it."
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee described the solution of the hijack crisis as an
occasion for cheer and joy and "doubly so because the ordeal of
our sisters and brothers, of the little children, held hostage by
the hijackers is nearing an end.
</P>
<P>
155 Passengers of the hijacked Indian jet have left for home
Friday evening from Kandhar aboard a special Indian plane.
</P>
<P>
The eight-day ordeal of the 155 passengers and crew of the
hijacked Indian plane came to a dramatic end minutes after the
External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh landed at Kandahar airport
in southern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Along with terrorism, the Indian leader told the nation, the
twin of poverty and illiteracy has to be wiped out.
</P>
<P>
He appealed the country to "seize the opportunities of the
coming era to emerge as a mighty nation whose strength shall lie
in her achievements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
