<HEADLINE> Writethru: Hijacking Drama Closes as Hijackers  Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The eight-day-long hijacking
drama involving an Indian airliner drew to a close Friday
afternoon as the hijackers released the hostages and surrendered
to the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
The hijacking ended after an agreement was reached between the
Indian government and the hijackers on the release of the hostages
in exchange for three jailed Muslim militants.
</P>
<P>
The five hijackers were seen to have left the plane, which had
been stranded at the Kandahar airport in Afghanistan over the past
week with more than 150 passengers and crew on board, sources from
Kandahar said.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Coordinator for Afghanistan Eric de Mul, who has
been involved in the negotiations, confirmed that under the
agreement ending the hijacking all three prisoners released by
India and the five hijackers had been handed to the Taliban
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The three militants had arrived in Kandahar earlier Friday
along with Indian Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh.
</P>
<P>
The eight were initially driven from the Kandahar airport. Mul
said that further moves were now in the hands of the Taliban
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the hostages were seen beginning to alight from the
plane which had been their prison since it was hijacked last
Friday during a flight from Kathmandu to New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Indian officials said the hostages will be flown to New Delhi
from Kandahar "very shortly."
</P>
<P>
The somewhat peaceful solution to the crisis was a result of
protracted negotiations between an Indian team, the Taliban, the
United Nations and the hijackers.
</P>
<P>
The Indian negotiating team arrived in Kandahar on Monday, the
third day after the plane landed there, when the hijackers
demanded the handover of the remains of a slain Muslim leader, the
release of 36 Muslim militants plus a 200 million U.S. dollar
ransom.
</P>
<P>
After five days of haggling, the hijackers agreed to exchange
the hostages for the release of three militants.
</P>
<P>
The hijacked plane had earlier landed at the Lahore Airport,
Pakistan, and a military base in Dubai. The hijackers shot dead
one passenger on board and had released 27 hostages at Dubai and
two at Kandahar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
