<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia records Higher Current Account Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's current
account surplus in the second quarter of 1999 increased by 24.6
percent over that in the preceding quarter, according to the
Statistics Department Friday.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in the quarter under review amounted to 14.2
billion ringgit (3.736 billion U.S. dollars) against 11.4 billion
ringgit (3 billion U.S. dollars) in the preceding quarter, the
Department said in a statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of 1999, the current account surplus
increased by 102.4 percent to 25.5 billion ringgit (6.71 billion U.
S. dollars) from 12.6 billion ringgit (3.315 billion U.S. dollars)
in the same corresponding period last year, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Department said net long term capital inflow of
6.0 billion ringgit (1.578 billion U.S. dollars) in the second
quarter of 1999 was almost four fold the net inflow of 1.6 billion
ringgit (421.052 million U.S. dollars) in the previous quarter on
increased inflow of both private and official long term capital.
</P>
<P>
Official long term capital net inflow surged to 3.6 billion
ringgit (0.947 billion U.S. dollars) in the second quarter of 1999
from 3.0 billion ringgit (0.789 billion U.S. dollars) in the
preceding quarter while private long term capital inflow in the
April to June 1999 period surpassed the first quarter 1999 level
of 1.3 billion ringgit (342.105 billion U.S. dollars) to reach the
2.4 billion ringgit (631.578 million U.S. dollars) mark,
representing an increase of 84.6 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
The first half of 1999 recorded an 11.8 percent increase in the
net long term capital inflow to reach 7.6 billion ringgit (2
billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
