<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Ships Back Wastes From Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government Friday
completed the removal of the entire wastes from the Philippines by
shipping them back to Japan.
</P>
<P>
The shipment was conducted much earlier than the deadline of
January 11, 2000, set by the governments of Japan and the
Philippines, the Japan Information and Cultural Center said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
On November 20, more than 2,000 tons of municipal and household
garbage, including syringes, adult diapers and sanitary napkins,
arrived in Manila from Japan in about 100 containers.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government has been making public its readiness to
cooperate with the Philippines on the waste issue and to fulfill
its obligation under the Basel Convention on the Transboundary
Movement of Hazardous Wastes and Its Disposal.
</P>
<P>
On December 19, Japan sent a fact-finding mission to Manila,
which also conducted on-site surveys and investigations at the
port of Manila.
</P>
<P>
The two governments later decided to accelerate the procedure
for the waste removal in keeping with the Basel Convention.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to establish a bilateral working group to
prevent a recurrence of such incidents through various efforts,
including the review of the export/import procedures of the two
countries under the Convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
