<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Reminds People of Challenges of New  Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Friday night that the people could rejoice
in welcoming the new century and millennium but they must beware
of the dangers of globalization that come with it.
</P>
<P>
"What is clear is that we are unprepared for the challenges of
the new millennium. We, especially the Malays, have the same old
habits and culture that caused us to be colonized for four-and-a-
half centuries," Mahathir said in his 2000 New Year message over
Radio Television Malaysia (RTM).
</P>
<P>
He called on the people to learn from the lessons of history
which require them to close ranks and be disciplined to face
attempts to recolonize the nation in the new millennium through
the globalization system of the west.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia had been colonized before because its people
were indiscplined, because of a jostle for places and power, and
now it would appear that the people had forgotten the lessons of
history.
</P>
<P>
"But the former colonial masters have plans to recolonize us.
This time a different method will be used to conquer our country.
This method is introduced as globalizations and a borderless world,
" Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He said they would control the economies of weak nations, own
banks and businesses and support free capital flow with the excuse
that poverty could be eradicated this way.
</P>
<P>
"What's strange is that while the free flow of capital
transcends borders, humans cannot. The poor will be imprisoned
without their own borders so as not to tarnish the rich nations.
</P>
<P>
"This is a borderless world, this is globalization. The rich
will become richer and the poor will work to enrich the wealthy.
Of course the poor nations are also free to penetrate the rich
markets but what do they have to sell in the rich markets that
have yet to be taken over by the giant investors from the wealthy
nations?" Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir held that the economic crisis in Malaysia and other
East Asian countries in July 1997 was a result of globalization
and was something real and not a forecast or fiction of the
imagination.
</P>
<P>
"They tried and nearly succeed but we were able to foil the
attempt this time and we were able to revive our country's economy.
But we are not safe yet. Attempts are still being made. If not for
the demonstrations against the WTO (World Trade Organization) in
Seattle (recently), maybe another part of our border will have
collapsed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysians of various races had decided that the
country would continue to have a credible government that could
face the challenges of the new millennium but the seeds of
disunity had been sown among the people and were spreading.
</P>
<P>
"When the government is concentrating on defending the nation
from external attacks, that's the best time to stab it in the back,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must be careful, close our ranks and set aside difference
that could split us as well as face the coming challenges with
fortitude and resilience," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He said history had shown that careful planning, a responsible
leadership, discipline, and training are needed for a struggle to
succeed and these could be inculcated in the local culture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
