<HEADLINE> Australia Enters New Millennium in Good Shape: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Australia is entering the new
millennium with a strong economy and with great cause for hope and
optimism, Prime Minister John Howard said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Presenting his message for the new millennium, Howard described
Australia as a peaceful, stable and cohesive society.
</P>
<P>
"Australia goes into the new century with an economy stronger
than it has been for decades. Unemployment is falling, growth is
very robust, inflation and interest rates are at their lowest for
years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The economy would be made even stronger by the introduction of
the new tax system on July 1 and this will deliver a 12-billion-
Australian dollar (7.92 billion U.S. dollars) tax cut to
Australians, the biggest ever, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the whole world will catch a glimpse of the
friendly Australian way when the country hosts the Olympic Games
next year.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Australians should remember those who were
not doing as well, including Aboriginal people and those in rural
and regional Australia who had been hurt by the process of
economic change.
</P>
<P>
"As we reflect on the opportunities which the future holds for
Australia, we should remember those Australians and those parts of
Australia which are not doing as well as the rest," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Strong though Australia's economy may be, by far the greatest
asset we take into the new century is our spirit as a people," he
said in his message.
</P>
<P>
"It is from that spirit that we derive the sense of mateship
displayed to each other in times of crisis and natural disaster.
It is that spirit which has moulded our practical 'can do'
approach to the problems and challenges we encounter as a nation,"
Howard added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
