<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zimbabwe Vows to Revive Economy in New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is determined to
revive its economy in the new year after it has gone through the
most difficult year since its independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Due to negative impacts by both internal and external factors,
the past year witnessed an all-round economic downturn in the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Its gross domestic product (GDP) for 1999 is predicted to fall
0.2 percent compared with that of the previous year while the
average inflation rate in the first 10 months of the year moved up
to 58 percent, which is double the figure for the same period a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit is around 7.5 percent of GDP for 1999 as
against the figure of 6.4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
With the interest rates climbing up over 60 percent,
Zimbabweans can hardly get loans from banks to invest in their
industrial and commercial sectors.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the adverse conditions in the world economy has also
constrained the potential growth of its economy. Depressed
international prices for most of its export commodities had an
adverse impact on balance of payment.
</P>
<P>
As a result of economic downturn, about 62 percent of the
population is considered poor and 45 percent is defined as very
poor. The unemployment rate has raised to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Despite hardships and economic difficulties, the Zimbabwean
government has time and again showed its strong determination to
reverse the economy which is believed not to collapse as some
foreigners' predictions.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the parliament a week ago, President Robert Mugabe
stressed that agriculture still retained its position as the major
contributor to economic growth and development.
</P>
<P>
At the just closed third National Congress of the ruling
Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front, the president
reaffirmed his government's land policy.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the government has pledged to provide more
funds for the land reform and resettlement program in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Now it is moving into top gear in the implementation of the
program to redistribute land, which has been set as one of the two
major tasks of the country next year.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government has also set indigenization of the
economy as another main task due to the country's poor performance
in its exports despite the depreciation of the Zimbabwean dollar
by about 50 percent since 1997.
</P>
<P>
The move is designed to boost production, improve exports and
stimulate its own industries by raising purchasing power of the
nationals.
</P>
<P>
The government has established the National Investment Trust of
Zimbabwe whose principal aim is to warehouse shares that can then
be purchased by the indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
In order to enable its economy to meet the required targets so
as to attract more foreign investment, the government has decided
to quicken its pace in the privatization of state enterprises,
which also offers fresh opportunities for the participation of the
indigenous people in the mainstream economy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government continues to urge large local and
foreign corporations to go into partnership wited the Reserve Bank of
Zimbabwe, central bank of the country, to reduce the current
punitive high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
As Mugabe has mentioned that the current economic downturn, job
creation, poverty alleviation and the HIV/AIDS pandemic constitute
 major challenges facing Zimbabwe in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's involvement in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC) war also aggregated its economic problems.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Zimbabwe sent 11,000 troops to the Congo
and treasury was spending in excess of three million dollars a
month since August 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe has pledged to withdraw his troops from the DRC once the
 timetable for the pullout of foreign troops is set.
</P>
<P>
With his full confidence in future, Mugabe has assured the
nation that the economy would revive next year so long as the
Zimbabwean people unite closely and work hard for social and
economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
