<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees Yeltsin's Resignation Dramatic But Not Surprise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government Friday
called the resignation of Russian President Boris Yeltsin dramatic
but not a complete surprise.
</P>
<P>
Before dawn, President Bill Clinton was notified about
Yeltsin's resignation by Sandy Berger, his assistant for national
security affairs.
</P>
<P>
After Yeltsin's resignation was confirmed in contacts with
Russian officials, White House spokesman James Fallin said "we
consider this a dramatic step." "While there is an element of
surprise it was not a complete one," he added.
</P>
<P>
Fallin cited numerous speculative reports in the Russian press
for several months about the 68-year-old Yeltsin's health problems.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, who will act as acting president
before the elections, is known to U.S. officials as a businesslike
professional. 
</P>
