<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
responding to the dramatic resignation of Boris Yeltsin, Friday
praised the Russian leader for working "together to advance common
interests" with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in a statement that his succession by Prime
Minister Vladimir Putin is evidence of Yeltsin's constitutional
achievements.
</P>
<P>
"We have had our differences, such as on Chechnya, but the
starting point of President Yeltsin and I has always been how
Russia and the United States could work together to advance common
interests," Clinton said, while extending his and Hillary Rodham
Clinton's warmest wishes to Yeltsin and his family.
</P>
