<HEADLINE> 1st lead: Passengers Leave Hijacked Indian Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Passengers of the hijacked
Indian jet have begun disembarking the aircraft after the masked
hijackers got down and drove away from the airport in Kandahar,
Afghanistan, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The five armed hijackers drove away from the airport in four-
wheel drive vehicles, apparently with released three militants who
were flown from New Delhi in exchange for the freedom of the 155
hostages held on the plane for eight days.
</P>
<P>
the relief A-320 Airbus carrying the hostages would depart from
Kandahar at 1800 hours local time, official sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Flight information clearance and air defense clearance had
already been obtained from Pakistan to facilitate the relief and
the special plane to fly over the neighboring country to reach
India, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The special Boeing-737 aircraft carrying External Affairs
Minister Jaswant Singh and the three hard-core militants reached
Kandahar at 1640 hours local time, they said.
</P>
<P>
PTI reported from Kandahar that the passengers were seen
descending from the plane to waiting buses at 5.40 pm and driven
away in a bus towards the Boeing-737.
</P>
<P>
Several Taliban Vehicles surrounded the hijacked Airbus as the
passengers began leaving, said PTI. 
</P>
