<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Major Chinese Cities Report Bad Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The quality of air in most
major Chinese cities worsened this week, according to the weekly
air quality report issued today by the China Environmental
Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
It was clearer and warmer in most cities. But the gentle breeze
could not help disperse pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Between December 24 and 30, Xiamen reported exceptionally clean
air, while Chengdu, Kunming, Wenzhou, Harbin, Lianyungang, Qingdao,
Suzhou, Haikou and seven other cities reported clean air.
</P>
<P>
Zhengzhou, Beijing, Shanghai, Chongqing, Shijiazhuang, Jinan
and seven other cities reported relatively poor air.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, Yinchuan, Urumqi and Taiyuan reported unhealthy air,
while Hohhot, Xining and Lanzhou reported hazardous air.
</P>
<P>
Lanzhou, Hohhot, Xining and 29 other cities listed suspended
particles as the major pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Nitrogen oxide was the major pollutant in Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou, Zhuhai and Shenzhen, while Chongqing, Guiyang, Yantai
and Qingdao claimed sulfur dioxide as the main culprit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
