<HEADLINE> Singapore will Speed Up Building-Up 3rd Generation Leadership: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong Friday stated his government will speed up building up
third generation leadership which is essential to turn Singapore
into a first-world economy and world-class home.
</P>
<P>
Goh made the statement in his new year message titled "Into The
Millennium With Confidence" where he reviewed major challenges
Singapore has experienced since its independence, briefed up the
current economic recovery in Singapore as well as the region,
offered a brighter prospect for year 2000 and highlighted what is
essential to achieving Singapore 21 vision.
</P>
<P>
Goh said Singapore's vision to become a first-world economy
and world-class home is a great challenge in the new millennium,
noting competing with developed economies in knowledge sectors is
different ball game altogether just as medals will be much harder
to win in the Olympics than in Southeast Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Billing leadership as a vital factor to sustain Singapore's
success, the prime minister said Singapore is fortunate to have
had good leadership in its first years of independence and a
second generation of leaders in guiding the country through the
recent regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We now have to identify new talent and build up the third
generation leadership," he said, adding "we already have the
beginning of this generation team."
</P>
<P>
Stressing that an honest and capable team at the helm is the
best guarantee that Singapore will continue to thrive in the new
millennium, the prime minister laid emphasis on the need "to
assemble, test out and train a full team as early as possible."
</P>
<P>
He also called Singaporeans to strengthen their roots and hold
together as a nation, saying "we cannot afford to become
deculturalized Our cultures and heritages are an important part of
our Singapore identity."
</P>
<P>
"Singapore needs to be a cohesive society and not just so many
individuals who can feel at home anywhere in the world," he
stressed. 
</P>
