<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Resigns, Hands Power to Putin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
stepped down Friday and handed his power to Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin in a move that is expected to boost the premier's
chance in winning the race for the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's resignation has been rumored many times earlier this
year, but the timing of the move came as a surprise to many
Russians preparing to enter a new year.
</P>
<P>
The 68-year-old Yeltsin, whose second term as the head of state
expires next June, told the nation in a televised address that he
would not "be clinging to power for another six months."
</P>
<P>
"Following a long and painful consideration I have taken a
decision. Today, on the last day of the outgoing century, I am
resigning," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have heard it said many times that Yeltsin will do
everything possible to remain in power and that he will never
surrender power to anyone," Yeltsin said. "All this is a lie."
</P>
<P>
He apologized to the Russians for failing to justify their
hopes.
</P>
<P>
The next presidential elections, originally scheduled for June,
will be held on March 27 instead, Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
Under Russian constitution, presidential elections should be
held within three months after the resignation of a sitting
president.
</P>
<P>
The offensive was launched in September following armed Chechen
incursions into neighboring Daghestan and a spate of apartment
building explosions that killed over 300 people in Moscow and two
other Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, born in Sverdlovsky (now Yekaterinburg) in 1931,
became the first popularly elected president of Russia in 1991. He
was reelected in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
His early resignation is believed to be further boosting
Putin's chance of entering the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Putin took office as premier last August, when Yeltsin
described him as his preferred successor.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister has canceled his trip to St. Petersburg,
where he had planned to spend the New Year's eve, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Putin is by far the most popular politician in post-Soviet
Russia. His rate of popularity has skyrocketed amid a federal
military campaign against rebels in the breakaway republic of
Chechnya
</P>
<P>
The news of Yeltsin's early step-down sent share prices soaring
in the Russian stock market, and the RTS-Interfax has shot up
seven percent to 176.9 during the last 10 minutes of trading,
Interfax reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Vacates Kremlin for Popular Putin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
stepped down Friday and handed his powers to Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin, his preferred successor who enjoys enormous
popularity among the Russians.
</P>
<P>
The resignation, although rumored for quite some time earlier
this year, came as a surprise as the world's largest country
prepares to enter the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's resignation, announced in a televised address to the
nation, is expected to further boost Putin's chance of winning the
race into the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Born on February 1, 1931, in Sverdlovsk in central-western
Russia, Yeltsin received his college education at the Urals M.
Kirov Polytechnic Institute.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 11, he lost the thumb and forefinger of his left
hand while disassembling a grenade that he and two friends had
gotten from a weapons warehouse.
</P>
<P>
Trained as an engineer, Yeltsin worked on various construction
projects from 1955-68. He joined the Soviet Communist Party in
1961 and became a member of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet in
1976.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin was appointed first secretary of the Moscow City
Communist Party Committee in 1985.
</P>
<P>
He became the first popularly elected president of Russia in
1991 and was reelected in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin had suffered from respiratory and heart troubles for
much of his presidency. In November 1996, he underwent quadruple
heart bypass surgery and was confined to the hospital for months.
</P>
<P>
In Friday's address on the ORT public television station,
Yeltsin denied the assertion that he does everything possible to
remain in power. "All this is a lie," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai-Based Veteran Scholars, Scientists Greet New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Writer Ke Ling, who was 91 years old this year, said he has
witnessed too many chaotic periods caused by repeated wars and
turmoils during his life time, so he can well appreciate and
understand how hard it was for China to have developed into today'
s prosperity and political stability.
</P>
<P>
"It is exciting to see China now full of auspicious signs and
with a stable political life, coupled with an economic takeoff and
social progress, and resumption of the exercise of its sovereignty
over Hong Kong in 1997 and over Macao ten days ago," said Ke, who
still writes essays.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-year-old Tan Jiazhen, a world-famous geneticist who just
recovered from a major ailment, is now in high spirits and still
has a quick mind.
</P>
<P>
"Of all the events of the past century, what impresses me most
are the earth-shaking changes that have occurred in the motherland
over the past two decades," said Tan, "the strategy of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics and the reform and opening-
up drive initiated by late leader Deng Xiaoping has made it
possible for China to attain economic development in a real sense.
"
</P>
<P>
Though now advanced in age, Tan said he would like to build a
still brighter future together with the younger generations.
</P>
<P>
Su Buqing, 97 years old, is a noted Chinese mathematician and
educator who is now confined to a hospital bed in Shanghai. Though
he cannot speak because of illness, he wrote "celebrating New Year
's Day 2000" on a white wooden board. He has been anticipating the
arrival of the new century, and used to say he would be very happy
to enter the new century with the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Su has used his personal savings to start a special math prize
for encouraging the development of promising younger, outstanding
mathematicians.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yuanhua, an art and literary theorist, is most concerned
about how to turn China into a better place to live in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
He believes that his motherland will make new breakthroughs in
the next century in the fields of genetics, astronomy, aerospace,
and telecommunications and electronics on the basis of scientific
and technological progress made in this century.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who is dedicated to the study of the history of thought
in modern China, calls for still greater attention to cultural and
ethical progress to help raise the quality of the Chinese people
as they pursue economic achievements.
</P>
<P>
The veteran scholars and scientists also stressed the
importance of carrying forward the fine traditions of the Chinese
nation and allowing intellectuals to play a full role in economic
construction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
