<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hong Kong Positioned for Economic Lift-Off (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Externally, exports of goods staged a significant upturn,
driven by the sharp rebound in exports of China's mainland, a
general pick-up in demand in the East Asian economies and a broad
strengthening in import absorption in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Exports of services likewise accelerated in growth, along with
the regional economic recovery, and the combined visible and
invisible trade balance should have yielded a considerably larger
surplus in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending picked up further, in tandem with the
recovery in overall economic activity and with the stable
employment situation.
</P>
<P>
On investment spending, the decline in expenditure on machinery
and equipment tended to taper, while public sector building and
construction output bounced back to positive growth, thereby
providing a partial offset to the continued slack in private
sector building activity.
</P>
<P>
The labor market has generally held stable, and the seasonally
adjusted unemployment rate in the third quarter of 1999 stood at 6.
1 percent while the underemployment rate was 3.1 percent,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The stock market also consolidated in the third quarter, but
regained strength in the latter part of October upon improved
market sentiment, and rallied to new post-crisis highs in December
upon China's accord with the United States on its accession to the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead, the Hong Kong economy should continue to benefit
from the revival of demand in East Asia, better economic
conditions in Europe, and sustained import absorption in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis served as a wake-up call for the
region and "Hong Kong has smelled the coffee," Financial Secretary
Donald Tsang Yam-kuen wrote in the latest issue of Economist
magazine.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is uniquely positioned to be the fastest-growing
economy in the world in the next 20 to 30 years, Sir John Bond,
group chairman of HSBC Holdings plc, said at a recent seminar on
Hong Kong's future economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hong Kong Positioned for Economic Lift-Off (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Most Hong Kong company executives are anticipating better
earnings this year. A recent executive survey of business
confidence by Dresdner RCM Global Investors showed 74 percent of
companies that participated would adjust their earning forecast
upward, with most of those banking on a rise of about 5 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
Dresdner believed the broader economy's recovery will be drawn
out for up to 12 months. Large multinational companies which have
weathered Asia's economic downturn have enjoyed better than
expected sales growth this year, according to Technomic
International.
</P>
<P>
"Multinationals are back to more normal business operations
today after almost two years of upheaval," Technomic Asia managing
director Steven Ganster said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors had high confidence in holding Hong Kong
dollar assets because short-term money market rates in the SAR
were lower than those in the United States and the local currency
was strong, Citibank country officer Chan Tze-ching said.
</P>
<P>
Dao Heng Bank senior economist Daniel Chan said the increasing
capital inflow was the result of an improvement in Hong Kong's
outlook following the signing of the Sino-U.S. agreement on China'
s entry into WTO.
</P>
<P>
The government has disposed of as much as 3.3 billion HK
dollars (423 million U.S. dollars) more of its share portfolio by
issuing additional Tracker Fund units in mid-November and on its
first day listing, 2.8 billion HK dollars (358 million U.S.
dollars) worth of units changed hands, representing 22 percent of
the total turnover of Hong Kong stock market.
</P>
<P>
Exchange Fund Investment (EFI) Director Eric Li Ka-cheung said
the new sales underlined the strength of the market's appetite for
the fund amid a surge that has been fueled by the good news on the
progress of China's entry into WTO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
