<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hong Kong Positioned for Economic Lift-Off (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- With a prudent forecast of
GDP growth in 1999, Hong Kong has for the first time positioned
itself for a post-recession economic lift-off since the Asian
financial crisis, economists said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a report on the economic forecast of Hong Kong in
2000, Sung Yun-wing, chairman of the Economic Department of the
Chinese University of Hong Kong, told a press conference that Hong
Kong's GDP growth rate in 1999 as a whole will be between 1.3
percent to 2.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
The department has maintained its econometric forecasting
program since 1979, and the forecasting model it created has since
1986 become a constituent model of the United Nations' on-going
large-scale research project linking together elaborate models on
a worldwide basis.
</P>
<P>
A brighter future for Hong Kong's economy in 2000 was predicted
by a group of senior economists of the department, with a GDP
growth rate of 5.4 percent for next year in a higher perspective
and 3.6 percent in a lower perspective.
</P>
<P>
Figures released in a recent report by the Census and
Statistics Department showed that Hong Kong's third-quarter real
GDP expanded by 4.5 percent year-on-year, surpassing market
expectations and forecast of 3 percent by domestic and overseas
economic analysts.
</P>
<P>
The recovery process of the Hong Kong economy has gathered
further momentum in the third quarter of 1999, and a crude initial
assessment suggests that the GDP should have attained a growth of
around 4.5 percent in real terms in the third quarter over a year
earlier, according to the government's third quarter economic
report.
</P>
<P>
Looking back upon Hong Kong's economic development as a whole,
Frank Leung, a local securities analyst, believed that the real
economic growth suggests that it is a genuine and sustainable
recovery rather than a bounce in year-on-year numbers solely as a
result of a low base in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The 1999 performance appears to be the beginning of a cyclical
upswing as prospects for 2000 also appear strong supported by a
higher rate of growth of world GDP and trade," said M.J. Quibria,
assistant chief economist of the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
