<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Raises Wages for Civil Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's civil servants will
be awarded salary increases of between 69 and 90 percent next
month on a sliding scale, while 20,000 posts will be abolished to
make way for lean and efficient government service.
</P>
<P>
Acting Public Service, Labour and Social Welfare Minister John
Nkomo said on Thursday that the government would save three
billion Zimbabwean dollars (78.9 million U.S. dollars) in salaries
and wages when holders of the 20,000 identified posts are retired
in a four-month exercise beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
Defending the hefty increases, he said it was an attempt to
cushion the civil servants from the harsh economic environment
being experienced in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The increases approved by the government have taken into
consideration the current rate of inflation, it is hoped the
increases will significantly improve the conditions of service in
the Zimbabwe Public Service as a whole, " he said.
</P>
<P>
The pay rise for civil servants comes just days after the
central bank warned that it would fuel inflation presently peaked
at 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Nkomo said the increases would not push up the rate of
 inflation if matched by raised productivity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
