<HEADLINE> Hijacked Indian Plane Engines Shut off in Freezing Temperatures  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 150 people aboard
the hijacked Indian Airlines Airbus faced freezing temperatures
early Friday when the engines on the jet shut down overnight.
</P>
<P>
The engines of the Indian Airbus-300 had been kept going almost
continuously since the plane landed at the Kandahar airport last
Saturday to keeping the heating system going.
</P>
<P>
The jet had been refueled Thursday and there was no immediate
explanation why the engines shut down.
</P>
<P>
The hijackers have demanded India release 36 Kashmiri militants
in Indian jails in exchange for the passengers and crew aboard the
plane, which was seized during a flight from Kathmandu to New
Delhi on Christmas eve.
</P>
<P>
The hijacking drama has entered its eighth day Friday with
reports from New Delhi saying that the hijackers have agreed to
release all passengers and crew members in exchange for three
Muslim militants.
</P>
<P>
Indian External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh has left New
Delhi for Kandahar, a city in Afghanistan, where the hijacked
plane has been staying for the past few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
