<HEADLINE> Nigerian Soldiers Return Home from Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Some 130 Nigerian officers and
men serving in the West African peace-keeping force of ECOMOG in
Sierra Leone have returned to Lagos in two navy warships and more
Nigerian troops will be back soon, local media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The returnee ECOMOG troops left Freetown, capital of Sierra
Leone, on Tuesday and arrived at the naval dockyard, Apapa Port of
Lagos on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
West Naval Command Rear Admiral Afolayan who welcomed the
returnees said that the warships brought only serving naval
personnel back from Sierra Leone, adding that arrangements were
made to bring back army and air force troops from Freetown.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the federal government has told Nigerian
air force and navy to get ready so that the ECOMOG troops could be
ferried back home before long.
</P>
<P>
About 1,400 of the 9,000 Nigerian troops currently in Sierra
Leone would remain for the disarmament process under a peace
agreement signed between the government and rebels of Sierra Leone
in July this year in the Togolese capital of Lome.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo has ordered the remaining
7,600 Nigerian troops in ECOMOG to return home while U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan reportedly sent an urgent message to
the president, urging Nigeria to keep her troops in Sierra Leone
to ensure stability in that country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
