<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ankara Takes Measures to Ensure Peaceful New Year Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Ankara Governor Yahya Gur has
declared that necessary precautions are being taken to ensure that
new year celebrations pass peacefully in the capital of Turkey,
Turkish Daily News reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Gur said measures, which will be
in force until January 3, 2000, have been taken on inter-city roads
and at airports, adding that police offices have been briefed on
how
to perform their duties by causing minimal disturbance to the
public.
</P>
<P>
The statement also contains a list of emergency telephone
numbers, covering security and police services, car accidents as
well as security-related problems in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The Ankara governor demanded that emergency departments at
hospitals will be working with extra staff.
</P>
<P>
Measures are also being taken at bus terminals in the capital.
Intra-city buses will be subjected to strict control and
unregistered
buses will not be allowed to use the roads.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Ankara Greater Municipality is taking
all necessary measures in terms of gas and water supply, adding
complaints in this regard can be reported to the municipal
services.
</P>
<P>
Turk Telekom, the giant Turkish telecommunication company, said
preventive measures have been taken for the first day of the year
but warned against New Year's Eve overload.
</P>
<P>
The company said Y2K is no longer a problem for it, adding
"emergency plans have been developed in case problems occur. During
the first three days of the new year, crisis centers will be in
charge to solve any problem."
</P>
<P>
But it said that it will not be responsible for overload due to
excessive demands for telecommunication during the period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
