<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IVO Urges Prevention of Rabies in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chamber of Istanbul
Veterinarians (IVO) has appealed for the establishment of urgent
rehabilitation units to prevent rabies incidents, reported Turkish
Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
IVO Chairman Tahsin Yesildere revealed that the disease caused
the deaths of three people in the country's largest city of
Istanbul in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
He added that they have found rabies microbes in 75 percent of
the 280 dogs examined at the Pendik Veterinary Medicine Control
Research Center's Rabies Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
He said that the number of rabies cases in dogs was previously
50-55 percent and that the 25-30 percent increase this year merits
serious public attention.
</P>
<P>
Yesildere said that every year, in 80 countries worldwide, more
than 40,000 people die of rabies and four million people are
treated for rabies. In Turkey, every year 90,000 people apply to
clinics on suspicion of rabies.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that that in England, Ireland and other EU states,
there is no rabies anywhere at all, adding that World Health
Organization (WHO) has not been informed of any death by European
countries for over 30-40 years.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the dreadful disease has recently spread
to Izmir, the third largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
An Anatolia News Agency report quoted officials from the Health
Ministry as saying that wolves, foxes, bears and donkeys are all
potential sources of the deadly disease although dogs are by far
the most common carriers.
</P>
<P>
It is not known whether the spread of the disease in the
western Turkey has any connection with the earthquakes that hit the
same region in the last few months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
