<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Twelve thousand policemen and volunteers will be deployed
throughout the nation from Friday until Sunday to protect against
possible millennium-related disasters.
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem, 3,000 extra police will help beef up security
around the Temple Mount in expectation of some 400,000 Muslim
worshipers there for Friday and Saturday, the last two days of
Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's registrar for associations, attorney Amiram Bogat,
has appointed an investigator to look into the three non-profit
associations linked to Ehud Barak's election for prime minister in
May.
</P>
<P>
Bogat said the main suspicion is that Barak's associates set up
the associations to channel donations for Barak's campaign in
breach of the party financing law.
</P>
<P>
Maariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh Thursday
confirmed for the first time that Israel will receive information
on missing Israeli Air Force navigator Ron Arad in return for
Lebanese prisoners released by Israel earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Barak is expected to raise the issue of missing soldiers with
Syria during next week's talks in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli President Ezer Weizman said Thursday that if a peace
agreement reached with Syria fails to win a majority support in a
national referendum, he will resign from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Members of the right wing has responded harshly to Weizman's
remarks, saying he is threatening the Israeli people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
