<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Economy Grows 5.6 Percent in 1999  h </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong Friday affirmed that his country's economy grew 5.6
percent in 1999 and will expand by between 4.5 to 6.5 percent for
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Goh made the statement in his new year message entitled "Into
The Millennium With Confidence.
</P>
<P>
Describing 1999 as a year of consolidation and recovery for
Asia, Goh said Singapore's economy grew 8.2 percent in the fourth
quarter of 1999 and achieved a 5.6 percent growth for 1999 as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
"The Singapore economy picked up vigorously, much faster than
we had expected," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the cost-cutting package adopted by his
government in November 1998 has strengthened the country's
competitiveness, reduced job losses and boosted exports, and it
was the decisive factor for Singapore's achievements in the year.
</P>
<P>
He said that external factors also helped the strong upswing in
electronics, the beginning of a turnaround in Japan, and continued
robust growth in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister predicted that the year 2000 will be a
better year, saying the economic outlook for 2000 is positive as
global economy should expand further.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's Ministry of Trade and Industry forecasts that the
country's economy will grow by 4.5 to 6.5 percent in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
