<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Expects Better Economy in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Socio-Economic Planning Secretary Felipe Medalla, who is
director general of the National Economic and Development
Authority (NEDA), said the Philippines remains on track in its
target to achieve a four percent growth in its Grss Domestic
Product (GDP) in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The country's GDP growth was recorded at 2.6 percent as of the
first nine months of 1999, while the growth of the Gross National
Product (GNP) reached 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The GNP includes the country's earnings from overseas sources,
such as the remittances of overseas Filipino workers.
</P>
<P>
"Our economic growth will be sustained. Our forecast is that we
can achieve a GDP growth of four percent next year," Medalla said
in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
In a report to Philippine President Joseph Estrada, Medalla
said the agriculture sector, which grew by 6.3 percent this year,
accounted primarily for the improvement of the economy in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Medalla noted that the lowest inflation rate was recorded in
November 1999 at 3.9 percent due to the improved agricultural
supply situation.
</P>
<P>
He said that over one million new jobs were created this year
with the agriculture sector generating some 691,000 of these jobs.
</P>
<P>
The NEDAchief also mentioned some other positive factors in the
country's economy, such as the decreasing interest rate and
unemployment rate, as well as the growth of foreign investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
