<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks Open on New Year's Weekend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Friday that banks, government offices and other critical agencies
will open this New Year's weekend to ensure sustained basic
services for the public when the new millennium arrives.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Commission on Year 2000 Compliance made this
clear as it reiterated confidence the Philippines is ready for the
millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, a directive has been issued
canceling leaves for some bank employees during the New Year's
weekend.
</P>
<P>
This extended tour of duty for concerned employees starts
Friday, December 31, and ends Sunday, the second day of the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Filemon Uriarte of the Department of Science and
Technology and head of the commission, allayed apprehensions that
the millennium bug, which affects older computer systems, would
still disrupt basic services despite government efforts to address
the problem.
</P>
<P>
Uriarte said the government is working double time to make sure
services in the seven critical sectors continue smoothly. These
are the sectors of telecommunications, utilities, transportation,
finance, government services, health care, and manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
The government has also set up a Y2K Action Center to address
possible emergencies arising from the Y2K bug. The action center
has been on 24-hour alert since December 28, and has links to the
National Disaster Coordinating Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
