<HEADLINE> Hijackers Agree to Free Hostages, Indian FM Leaves for Kandahar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Hijackers have agreed to
release all passengers in exchange of three Kashmir Muslim
militants, Brajesh Mishra, Principal Secretary to the Prime
Minister said Friday.
</P>
<P>
External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh left here Friday for
Kandahar, Afghanistan Friday to help resolve the week-long
hijiacking crisis.
</P>
<P>
Singh told reporters: "I am leaving for Kandahar shortly to
assist the negotiating team" and assess the ground situation.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a two-hour meeting of the cabinet
committee on security at the prime minister's residence.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by Defense Minister George
Fernandes and the Chiefs of the three services.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reviewed the latest situation on the crisis, Singh
said.
</P>
<P>
Indian negotiators have already completed five rounds of talks
with the hijackers of the Indian Airlines aircraft and are likely
to resume the sixth round Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
