<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesia's Economy Back to Growth Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The optimistic prediction was based on the number of rise of
consumption goods imported for the country's middle class
community.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, value of Indonesia's export has risen in October
1999 to 4.587 million U.S. dollars or 2.13 percent higher than
September, while import value in the same time was 2.028 millions
dollars or lower than September which reached to 2.127 millions
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the rising of share prices with a 70 percent gain
on the JSX (Jakarta Stock Exchange), and the stabilization of the
rupiah at level of Rp 7.000 per dollar and the falling of
benchmark interest rates to 12 percent per annum have become
evidence that Indonesia's macroeconomic conditions have been
improving.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government predicted that the country's economy
in 2000 will grow by 2 to 3.5 percent, with an inflation rate
between 4 and 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's gross domestic product contracted by 13.6 percent
in 1998 and posted an inflation of as high as 75 percent, bringing
the country's per capita income to about 400 U.S. dollars from a
pre-crisis level of over 1,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A noted economist of the Center for Strategic and International
Studies (CSIS) Hadi Susatro even said that Indonesia could expect
an economic growth of over 4 percent in 2000, or higher than the
government's assessment.
</P>
<P>
"The national production capacity which is currently idle, will
have to resume in 2000 on the grounds that international
confidence in Indonesia has been restored," Susastro said recently.
</P>
<P>
He added that prospect for economic growth in the East Asia
region in 2000 looked good and it would also favorably affect the
Indonesian economy.
</P>
<P>
An economic journal also wrote that "the economic growth during
this year appears to show an indication towards a better
improvement."
</P>
<P>
The domestic political stability since the new government
established in October has been a main factor prompting trade
activities on the JSX. Superior shares such as Astra International
(a car maker company) increased sharply in October from 900 rupiah
to 3,375 rupiah (increased by 36 points)," the Escom journal wrote
in its December edition.
</P>
<P>
With the support from other countries as well as the IMF (
International Monetary Fund) and the World Bank, the government
could be optimistic that its economic target would be met this
year.
</P>
<P>
The National Investment Board (BKPM) also predicted that
investment in Indonesia in 2000 would recover thanks to the
improvement of the political situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic that investment in the country will recover
in 2000. Investment in Indonesia, both domestic and foreign, will
keep rising next year," Deputy Chairman of BKPM Andung
Nitimihardjo said.
</P>
<P>
But even with the economic improvement, the country is
currently still troubled by serious problems resulting from not
only the economic crisis and social gap, but also religious,
racial, regional and other constraints.
</P>
<P>
The banking recapitalization problem seems to be the most
urgent task that should be done by the government. Apart from
economic issues, the country also has to deal with serious matters
such as disintegration threats, corruption and ethnic jealousy.
</P>
<P>
The continuing ethnic bloodshed in Ambon, capital of Maluku
province, could also be an obstacle for the economic recovery. It
seems to be a new challenge for the country in the third
millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
