<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN -- Germany is expected to record a 2.5 to 3 percent
economic growth in the year 2000, with a yearly jobless total of
less than four million, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said here
Thursday in a interview with the newspaper Handelsblatt.
</P>
<P>
"It means a big step towards maturity," said Schroeder,
pointing out that since 1996, unemployment has always hovered
above that figure. "But it does not mean that we have passed the
crisis," he added, saying that the government will keep working
for a distinct and consecutive reduction in unemployment. The tax
reform will continue so that enterprises will be less burdened and
stronger in global competition, he added. (Germany-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma on Thursday appointed
three deputy prime ministers and 11 ministers with eight members
of the outgoing cabinet, including foreign, defense, interior and
finance ministers, remaining on their posts, an announcement from
the Presidential Office said.
</P>
<P>
Yuri Yekhanurov, who had served in earlier cabinets as economic
minister and the head of Ukraine's privatization agency, was
appointed first deputy prime minister. Yulia Tymoshenko and Mykola
Zhulynsky, both senior members of parliament, were named deputy
prime minister. (Ukraine-PM-Appointment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- More Burundian refugees are fleeing into
Tanzania's west Kigoma Region as the security situation worsens in
their homeland, the top official of the U.N. refugee agency in the
region said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"A total of 12,720 Burundian refugees had arrived in Kigoma by
December 29 compared to 5,365 last month," said Marion Roche, head
of a sub-office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in
Kigoma. "The high number this month is probably a reflection of
the worsening stability in Burundi," said Roche. She said most
refugees paint a gloomy picture of the situation in Burundi,
accusing rebels of burning houses along the border and the army of
harassing people. (Tanzania-Burndi-Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- The European Union decided Thursday to grant a
total of 209 million euros (some 211 million U.S. dollars) to
Romania to support the structural adjustment of its mining
enterprises and infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 100 million euros will be offered for the
structural adjustment and reemployment as part of the western
countries' 1999 "Phare Program" to aid central and east European
countries. The other 109 million will mainly be used to develop
infrastructure, promote the privatization process, strengthen
border trade and reform the social insurance system. (Romania-EU-
Loan) 
</P>
</TEXT>
