<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: On the Eve of New Millennium in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- If there is any celebration of
the new millennium in Bangladesh at all, that will be at the non-
governmental level, as the government has announced no official
programs so far to greet the dawn of the new century and the new
millennium, which is less than one day away.
</P>
<P>
For the government, the priority at the moment is how to foil
the opposition's oust-government movement which has gained
momentum recently, marked by the first summit of the four-party
opposition alliance at end-November.
</P>
<P>
And for the ordinary people, January 1, 2000 only means another
day, which will not be much different from any other day they have
lived.
</P>
<P>
Three calendars are practiced in Bangladesh, the Gregorian
calendar which will enter the third millennium on Saturday, the
Hegira calendar, now in the year 1420 and commonly practiced by
the Muslim community, and the Bengali calendar which is now in the
year 1406.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, euphoria has gripped the young people, especially
university students, who are making preparations for the
celebration of the zero hours before entering into the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
Traders and retailers in the capital city of Dhaka have
expanded their business activities taking the advantage of the
occasion and of the month of Ramadan, which is followed by Eid-ul-
Fitr, the most important festival for Muslims all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Traffic jams have become a common scene in Dhaka, as the
government has shortened the office time from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. to
9 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. during Ramadan and many people have gone out
on a shopping spree, taking advantage of the special offers by
traders.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here said the main places of attraction in
Bangladesh for the young generation are the sea-beach resorts in
Khuakata, in southern Patuakhali district and in southeastern Cox'
s Bazar, from where they can witness the last setting of the sun
in the 20th century and the first sunrise of the 21st century and
the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
But the euphoria seems to have been confined among the middle-
and high-income groups only. The advent of the millennium could
generate little interest among the poor, who still account for
nearly half of the country's population of over 120 million at the
end of this millennium.
</P>
<P>
"What's there in the coming of a millennium or going of the
other? All I have to think of is earning my bread working day-long.
There is no scope for me at least to waste a bread-earning day by
celebrating a mere sunset or a sunrise," rickshaw-puller Shamsu
Mia said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export of Tea Down, of Frozen Food up in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's tea export fell
drastically while the export of frozen food rose slightly during
July-September period, the first three months of the current 1999-
2000 fiscal year, The Economic Observer reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The country earned 189 million taka (about 3.7 million U.S.
dollars) by exporting 2.28 million kilograms of tea during the
three-month period, 62.2 percent down from that of the
corresponding period of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Experts blamed the fall of both demand and price of Bangladeshi
tea in the international market for the export fall.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Tea Board has fixed a target of 2 billion taka (
about 39.2 million dollars) from tea export during the current
fiscal year. The country produces 55 million kilograms of tea
annually, and slightly more than half of the amount is consumed
domestically.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of the current fiscal year, the
country earned 122.8 million dollars from frozen food export, 0.25
percent higher than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Exporters said the prices of frozen food in the international
markets remained fair due to good demand in the three-month period.
The government has aimed to export 296 million dollars' worth of
frozen food this fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Trekkers Reach South Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 31 (Xinhua)-- Singapore's South Pole team
members reached the South Pole on Friday to become the first four
Singaporeans to set foot on the southernmost point of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
It took the four members, led by expedition leader Khoo Swee
Chiow, about 65 days to trek on foot about 1,100 kilometers before
reaching the South Pole.
</P>
<P>
On hearing the news, Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong
congratulated the team on the success, expressing the hope that
the expedition will inspire other Singaporeans to dare and achieve.
</P>
<P>
The Singaporeans must have the guts, the spirit and the
capability to face their own challenges in life, he said.
</P>
<P>
For a while, the trekkers met with a series of setbacks and no
one was sure if they could make it.
</P>
<P>
These included being delayed in Punta Arenas, Chile, because of
bad weather, being slowed down considerably by huge ice-ridges,
and even being snowed in by blizzards on Antarctica. 
</P>
</TEXT>
