<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Curfew Clamped on Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- In an attempt to create peace
and order in Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku province, a
curfew has been imposed on the city, according to national
newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the Maluku Military Region Brig. Gen. Max Tamaella
Thursday issued a rule forbidding Ambon residents to leave their
homes between 10:00 p.m. and 06:00 a.m. local time the next day.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with the Muslim fasting month, residents may
leave their homes only for emergency reasons, without having to
cross their neighborhood borders," Tamaella said.
</P>
<P>
He said the security authorities also prohibited any gathering
of people which involved more than 10, without acceptable purposes.
Gatherings as part of religious practices were exempted.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that violence in Ambon subsided on Thursday,
but clashes continued in other parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
Fighting is still going on and at least 265 persons have been
killed in clashes between Christians and Muslims on Halmahera
island in North Maluku over the last three days.
</P>
<P>
The number of casualties brought the death toll in sporadic
communal clashes across the spice islands of Maluku to nearly 340
since the new wave of violence broke out on Sunday, just after a
peaceful Christmas.
</P>
<P>
In its press release, the Indonesian Military information
service said about 360 buildings, including mosques, churches,
were burned down, while nearly 12,000 people sought refuge at the
nearest military installations following the violence that rocked
the district of Tobelo in Halmahera island.
</P>
<P>
According to the Jakarta Post, the riots in Tobelo ceased when
dozens of military troops arrived to restore order there. But
tension remained high, with security personnel standing on alert
across the town.
</P>
<P>
The violence followed similar clashes in Ambon where at least
63 people were killed and more than 100 were injured this week.
</P>
<P>
Unrest was also reported on Haruku island, east of Ambon, where
eight people have been killed in the violence since Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Maluku has been the site of bloody communal violence since the
beginning of the year, and nearly 1,000 people have died. Hundreds
of shops, offices, homes and other buildings, including many
churches and mosques, have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid and Vice President Megawati
Soekarnoputri visited Ambon on December 12, pleading for an end to
the bloodshed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
