<HEADLINE> Canadians Claim First to Usher in New Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Canadians claim themselves the
first to usher in the 21st century, while in South Pacific, Pitt
Island, Tonga and Fiji are bickering over which to see the first
sunrise of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The Inuit people in the country's northernmost community at
Grise Fiord, Nunavut, had the world's earliest New Year's Eve at
the end of October, when the sun last shone on their homes on
Ellesmere Island, the country's National Post said.
</P>
<P>
The sun will reappear as late as in the second week in February
at Grise Fiord, which is located at 76 degrees north latitude.
</P>
<P>
In Canada's western province of Alberta, people in Red Deer are
celebrating New Year's Eve Thursday night for fear of the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
The city's First Night Festival Committee said it decided to
hold New Year's activities on December 30 because the city's 65,
000 people asked it to develop a detailed contingency plan in case
of worst Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the country, Canadians observe the universal time,
with "electric evening" and fireworks to be displayed as the
centerpiece of celebrations at Friday mid-night in Ottawa, as well
as in the country's provincial capitals from Vancouver to Toronto.
</P>
</TEXT>
