<HEADLINE> Sweden Offers Permanent Seat for World Anti-Doping Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Swedish Sports Minister
Ulrica Messing suggested Thursday that her country provide a
permanent home for the newly inaugurated World Anti-Doping Agency
(WADA) in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
"Sweden has the knowledge and the competence, and this nation's
credibility in fighting drugs and doping are factors that might
work to the advantage of Sweden," the sports minister told The
Associated Press (AP).
</P>
<P>
Ever since its establishment last month in Lausanne, the WADA
has been criticized by many as being too close to the
International Olympic Committee (IOC) and it should be moved. A
number of European cities have expressed interest and the IOC
plans a bidding process for a permanent seat.
</P>
<P>
Messing said she believed the WADA headquarters would be moved
after 2001 and Sweden would submit an application after the IOC
specified its criteria.
</P>
<P>
She said WADA should be moved from its present location for
propriety's sake.
</P>
<P>
"For one it is good to show an independent stance in relations
with IOC," Messing said. "But I also think it is improper to have
such an agency in a country like Switzerland, which has such
liberal views on drugs. This is a matter of credibility."
</P>
<P>
The Swedish government recently almost doubled the annual
financial allocations to its anti-doping efforts from kronor 6.6
million (767,000 U.S. dollars) to 11 million kronor (1.28 million
U.S. dollars), the AP report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
