<HEADLINE> EU Grants 209 Million Euros to Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Union decided
Thursday to grant a total of 209 million euros (some 211 million U.
S. dollars) to Romania to support the structural adjustment of its
mining enterprises and infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 100 million euros will be offered for the
structural adjustment and reemployment as part of the western
countries' 1999 "Phare Program" to aid central and east European
countries.
</P>
<P>
The other 109 million will mainly be used to develop
infrastructure, promote the privatization process, strengthen
border trade and reform the social insurance system.
</P>
<P>
A total of nine related memorandums were signed by EU
representative Fokion Fotiadis and Romanian Foreign Minister Petre
Roman, the Romanian news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Fotiadis said the EU will tremendously increase its financial
aid to Romania as negotiations on Romania's admission into the EU
draw near so that the country could catch up with the EU's other
members in the political and economic fields as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU will offer Romania 640 million euros (about
650 million U.S. dollars) in 2000. 
</P>
