<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Plans Major Road Projects for Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has planned two
major road development projects for next year in suburban Colombo
and in the south to help attract more investors through speedy
transport, the Road Development Authority (RDA) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the RDA said the two projects are the 29 km
Colombo-Katunayake Expressway and the 128 km Southern Express
Highway.
</P>
<P>
The two projects, which will get off the ground in April and
October next year, respectively, will generate 15,000 jobs,
representing the largest ever road development projects in the
country, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
A cabinet appointed tender board has recommended a 125 million
U.S.dollars offer forwarded by a joint Belgian-Chinese party for
the construction of the Colombo-Katunayake Expressway.
</P>
<P>
Preliminaries on the expressway, including the environment
impact assessment and land acquisition have been completed.
Designs, tenders and funding proposals are under evaluation.
</P>
<P>
For the Southern Express Highway project, the environment
impact assessment and land acquisition have been completed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a concessional loan of 89.4 million dollars from the
Asian Development Bank (ADB) has been obtained for the project
which will cost 296.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government, Swedish International Development
Agency and the Nordic Development Fund will co-finance 128 million
dollars while the balance 78.8 million dollars will be met by the
Sri Lankan government.
</P>
<P>
During the past five years the development and maintenance of
the national road network has been considerably stepped up as lack
of speedy transport is the major impediment to the development of
the country.
</P>
<P>
A total of 700 kilometers of road have been rehabilitated and
construction work is in progress on 61 bridges with the assistance
of the World Bank, ADB, Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund (OECF)
of Japan and Kuwait Fund.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, 86 road sections and 79 bridges have already been
developed with local funds.
</P>
<P>
Budget allocations have also been made available for the
improvement of estates roads and the development of provincial and
rural roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
