<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China Centenary Bell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The giant bronze China
Centenary Bell, the largest in the nation, will be rung at the
China Centenary Altar in Beijing to greet the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The 50-ton bell is 6.8 meters high and 3.38 meters in diameter,
bigger than the famous 579-year-old Yongle Bell in the Big Bell
Temple in northwestern Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The China Centenary Bell is installed at the China Centenary
Altar in western Beijing -- the only symbolic structure in China
to welcome the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The idea for the bell originated with some Chinese scholars,
including Fei Xiaotong, Qian Weichang, and Ding Shisun, and the
bell was designed by Xiao Hong, who won the top prize in the
design contest for flags and emblems for the Hong Kong and Macao
Special Administrative Regions. Fei Xiaotong named the giant bell.
</P>
<P>
The bell is inscribed with the national anthem, the patterns of
the Great Wall, 56 peony flowers symbolizing the unity of China's
56 ethnic groups, and two dragons representing China's long
history of civilization.
</P>
<P>
"Major Historical Events of the 20th Century" is inscribed on
the bell. Historians from Beijing University wrote 4,474 words
describing the history of the Chinese people in their struggles
for independence, democracy, and prosperity since 1900.
</P>
<P>
The China Centenary Bell is a product of joint efforts by
several plants and research institutes. Its casting was completed
on December 17 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally in China, bells are used to record historic
events, eulogize people's merits and virtues, and give advice, and
they are rung during major festivals and grand ceremonies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China Centenary Altar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The China Centenary Altar, a
structure symbolizing China's 5,000-year-old civilization and its
people's wishes for the new millennium, now stands serenely in
western Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The altar is located between the Military Museum of the Chinese
People's Revolution and China Central Television, with Yuyuantan
Park up the north and the Beijing West Railway Station down the
south.
</P>
<P>
Construction of it began on October 10, 1998. Composed of the
main building, a bronze-paved path, a Sacred Flame Square and
several other structures, the altar complex covers a total area of
4.5 hectares.
</P>
<P>
A 34.6-ton white marble stele, nine meters long and 1.05 meters
high, stands at the southern entrance of the altar, inscribed with
an epigraph written by President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
At the back of the stele is a round square, 35 meters in
diameter and one-meter deep below the ground. The Sacred Flame, a
symbol of the origin and eternal nature of Chinese civilization,
will be lit at midnight on a platform in the middle of the square.
Two streams of water, each flowing at the west and east of the
square, represent the Yangtze and Yellow rivers, known as the
mother rivers of China.
</P>
<P>
The 270-meter-long and 15-meter-wide path connects the square
and the main building of the altar. 5,000 pieces of bronze relief,
each representing one year since the beginning of Chinese history
in about 3,000 B.C., are laid in the middle of the path.
</P>
<P>
The main altar structure, 27 meters high and 85 meters in
diameter, is a five-storey building with two floors below the
ground. It is made up of a revolving altar weighing more than 3,
200 tons and a long cloister surrounding it, which symbolize
heaven and earth. The altar is the largest and heaviest of its
kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
A 27.6-meter-high symbolic probe that is nailed to the oblique
plane of the rotary altar is pointing to the sky, indicating the
Chinese people's spirit of exploration.
</P>
<P>
The China Centenary Altar is an artistic combination of Chinese
architecture, gardens, frescos and carvings, and will serve as a
window to help people of other countries understand the 5,000-year-
old splendid art and culture of China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fully Prepared for Y2K Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Professionals in the offices
of the China Y2K Problem Contingency Office who have been hustling
and bustling these days began Thursday a five-day monitoring of
possible problems related to Y2K.
</P>
<P>
"Though confident of solving the computer millennium bug
problem, we are preparing for the worst," said Zhang Qi, director
of the emergency headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Today is the last day of the millennium, and the Chinese
government, in order to facilitate the solution, has made the day
a holiday, with banks and stock markets closed.
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted that 20 crucial industries including banking,
securities, and electricity grids have all worked out
corresponding contingency plans and implementation schemes.
</P>
<P>
The millennium, or Y2K, problem affects older computers which
only recognize the last two digits of the year, possibly
triggering failures when the date rolls over to 2000.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the country's central bank, has
organized three nationwide out-of-service tests for the banking
industry in cooperation with securities, insurance, and other
financial agencies.
</P>
<P>
A central bank official said that the country's banking system
is now basically ready for the transition, and no cash runs have
occurred so far.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a smooth transition, the bank has also formulated
contingency measures such as preparing adequate cash for customers.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jianfeng, director of the General Administration of Civil
Aviation of China, said he will take a cross-millennium flight
aboard a Chinese airliner. "I am confident in China's civil
aviation," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Zhang didn't rule out the possibility that something will
happen somewhere, and added that her office will try every
possible way to keep any losses to a minimum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Honduras to Toughen Anti-drug Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Honduras expects a further
hardening of the laws next year to efficiently combat drug
trafficking, an official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Alfredo Landaverde, general secretary of the Anti-Drug National
Commission, said a new law bill will seek -- in the war against
money laundering -- the cancellation of bank secrecy when the
courts request it.
</P>
<P>
Up to now the laws of the country only permit the seizure of
aircraft and other transportation equipment related to drug
trafficking, but say nothing about assets.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Roberto Flores announced earlier that Honduras
and the United States will sign an agreement in 2000 to combat
drug trafficking in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Convicted Honduran drug trafficker Ramon Matta, imprisoned in
the United States, has increased his assets in Honduran commercial
sectors, according to police.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) said that some
drug traffickers have businesses in Honduras because of the lack
of teeth in the laws against drug trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
