<HEADLINE> U.S. Flag Hauled Down Unexpectedly in Panama Canal Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The last U.S. national
flag in the Panama Canal zone was hauled down at 17:00 local time
Thursday afternoon, 19 hours earlier than expected. No public
explanation was made.
</P>
<P>
The local RPC radio said the U.S. government requested the
early pulling down of the flag, which had originally been
scheduled for midday Friday, December 31, when the Panamanian flag
was to be raised by President Mireya Moscoso.
</P>
<P>
Under the Torrijos-Carter treaties signed between the two
countries in 1977, December 31 was the day when the U.S.
government formally returns the interoceanic waterway to the
Panamanian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Attendance at the small hauling ceremony in front of the Canal
Administration building was strictly limited, with the U.S. side
represented by Ambassador Simon Ferro and Canal Commission
managing board chairman Louis Caldera, who is also U.S. Army
general secretary. The Panamanian side was led by President
Moscoso.
</P>
<P>
Neither the Panamanian government nor the U.S. embassy in this
country has made any statement on the matter, sparking media
speculation that Washington was shy of lowering it flag in the
eyes of the general public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
