<HEADLINE> Nigerian Millennium Celebration in High Gear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- A jubilant national costume
display staged here Thursday by children from Nigeria's 37 states
pushed the country's millennium celebration into high gear.
</P>
<P>
The kids, dressed in colorful costumes of Nigeria's more than
200 nationalities, paraded around Eagles Square in the country's
capital Abuja, where President Olusegun Obasanjo was inaugurated
as the first civilian president on May 29, ending 15 years of
military rule in the country.
</P>
<P>
Groups of children stopped in front of the VIP platform to
recite their millennium wishes.
</P>
<P>
One girl said a united and prosperous Nigeria was among her
favorite wishes, while another from Abuja told the laughing
audience that she hoped her country would be Y2K free.
</P>
<P>
Stella Obasanjo, the country's first lady, was present at the
event, along with many ministers and other dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday evening a "Gala night," characterized by showcase
of attractive performance of Nigeria's traditional music and
delicacies, enlivened the Sheraton Hotel, one of the best in the
West African country's capital.
</P>
<P>
Other celebrations are also underway in other parts of the
country, which has a population of about 120 million.
</P>
<P>
A boat regatta was held last week in Oron of the country's
southwest Akwa Ibom State on the Niger delta. Hundreds of colored
and lavishly bedecked dug-out canoes representing different
riverine states along the Niger took part in the two-day
competition.
</P>
<P>
Three dramas are being staged in Abuja and other major cities
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The plot of "OBA Ovonramwen," one of the plays, depicts the
saga of Benin Kingdom's heretic resistance against the British
colonial invasion at the turn of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the new millennium, an all night carnival
accompanied with a fireworks display will take place on Eagles
Square.
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo is expected to attend the event and make a
speech on the eve or early morning of the first day of the new
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
