<HEADLINE> Schroeder Optimistic About German Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Germany is expected to record a
2.5 to 3 percent economic growth in the year 2000, with a yearly
jobless total of less than four million, Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder said here Thursday in a interview with the newspaper
Handelsblatt.
</P>
<P>
"It means a big step towards maturity," said Schroeder,
pointing out that since 1996, unemployment has always hovered
above that figure.
</P>
<P>
"But it does not mean that we have passed the crisis," he added,
saying that the government will keep working for a distinct and
consecutive reduction in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The tax reform will continue so that enterprises will be less
burdened and stronger in global competition, he added.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said his coalition government will not break the
policy of continuity, and a zero deficit increase will be its
medium-term objective.
</P>
<P>
As to the controversial pension reform plan, Schroeder stressed
that it is of great importance in liberating enterprises and
creating new jobs.
</P>
<P>
His government has proposed keeping the pension increase rate
lower than the inflation rate in the coming two years.
</P>
<P>
The government will come up with a concrete pension reform plan,
following consultation among all parties, by the coming summer and
have it implemented by the end of 2000, Schroeder said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
