<HEADLINE> Hawks Again Suspend Guard Isaiah Rider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- NBA Atlanta Hawks guard
Isaiah Rider was suspended by the team today for the second time
this season, one day after a profanity-laced tirade.
</P>
<P>
Rider failed to join the Hawks for Wednesday's flight to
Detroit and
finally caught up with the team this morning.
</P>
<P>
Rider said he missed the Wednesday 6 p.m. flight by five
minutes and normally the plane does not leave until 15 or 20
minutes after its scheduled departure time.
</P>
<P>
"I felt I was left as a punishment," Rider said. "I got here
today, I was expecting to play. I didn't think I would start. I
thought I would be fined but I didn't expect this."
</P>
<P>
Rider spoke to the media after taking part in a players-only
meeting. Afterward, he left the facility as per team rules.
</P>
<P>
Hawks spokesman Arthur Triche said Rider has been suspended
indefinitely. ESPN is reporting he will sit for a minimum of two
games. Jimmy Jackson took Rider's place in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
The Hawks' suspension of their leading scorer comes about 24
hours after Rider questioned his teammates' commitment following a
116-89 home loss to Indiana, Atlanta's eighth setback in 10 games.
</P>
<P>
Rider remained on the court for 10 minutes after the final horn,
slumped against the scorer's table.
</P>
<P>
Today, Rider said teammates were laughing on the bench during
the game and he had a hard time with that reaction.
</P>
<P>
Rider's first season with the Hawks has been an eventful one.
He is 10th in the NBA in scoring at 23.0 points per game but
already has been suspended and benched before reclaiming his spots
as starting shooting guard and top offensive option.
</P>
<P>
Rider was suspended by the team for a November 16 game against
Charlotte after missing a practice. He was late for training camp
after refusing to board a smaller plane to Chattanooga, Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
Acquired this summer from Portland in a deal for All-Star Steve
Smith, Rider has been suspended by the NBA and his team several
times during his seven-year career and has had more than one run-
in with the law. He was charged with possession of marijuana and
unlawful possession of cellular telephones in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Rider, 28, entered the season with a career scoring average of
18 points per game for Minnesota and Portland. He was chosen fifth
overall by the Timberwolves in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
