<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Venezuela Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela received 515.8
million U.S. dollars in foreign investment this year, a growth of
almost 48 percent over 1998, a government official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, Foreign Investment Superintendent Luis
Ortega said the figure shows that the government of President Hugo
Chavez has stabilized the national economy, which has become
attractive to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Colombia was Venezuela's leading source of foreign capital this
year, with 22.9 million dollars, followed by Switzerland with 15.6
million dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
The trade sector absorbed most of the foreign investment with
28.7 million dollars, followed by the manufacturing industry, with
21.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Citing favorable economic conditions, Ortega noted that the
country's inflation rate dropped from 38 percent in 1998 to 20
percent this year, the balance of payments registered a surplus
and international reserves grew to 15.5 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
