<HEADLINE> IAAF Chief Says Marathon an Athletic Pilgrimage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Rome Millennium Marathon, to
be held on the first day of the New Year, represents an "athletic
pilgrimage" closely connected to the Holy Year celebrations, neo-
president of the International Amateur Athletics Federation Lamine
Diack said THursday.
</P>
<P>
In his first official speech as IAAF chief, Diack said that "
the marathon is a symbol of the exhausting physical and spiritual
progress which the athlete makes in seeking the finishing line.
This is why the Pope has agreed to the twinning of the great
Jubilee religious event with our sporting event."
</P>
<P>
Here in Rome to officially present the Marathon, Diack also
said that the year 2000 should be dedicated to encouraging
athletics in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"Athletics cannot be a purely European event. It touches and
involves all the countries in the world. IAAF will work hard
across the globe, especially in Asia and Africa, where the human
potential is enormous and so far little exploited," he said.
</P>
<P>
Diack is the successor of Primo Nebiolo, who died of a heart
attack at the age of 76 on November 6.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,500 athletes are expected to take part in the 42-km Rome
Millennium Marathon.
</P>
<P>
The race will start in St. Peter's Square, where participants
will receive the blessing of Pope John Paul II and the necessary "
spiritual encouragement", as Diack said. 
</P>
