<HEADLINE> Lebanese Welcome New Millennium in High-tech Extravaganza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Lebanese and
foreigners Friday night flocked to the coastal street in Beirut in
a high-tech extravaganza to welcome the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The main celebration site, about 80,000 square meters, boasts a
huge center stage, a 90-meter-long wall for image projections, a
giant dance floor, a VIP lounge, with restaurant and food courts,
and tents which held about 6,000 spectators.
</P>
<P>
There are also standing place for at least a few thousand more.
</P>
<P>
A dazzling light show lit up the damp night, the fireworks
filled the sky and laser beams swept across the entire city.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian singer Amro Diab, one of the most popular in the Arab
world, opened the celebrations with his velvety voice and pushed
the country's 15-day celebrations to the climax.
</P>
<P>
Outside the site, throngs of people squatted on the sidewalks or
stood in front of the wide screen to get a view of the concert.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said this was the biggest and longest-running party
in Lebanon's history, which started on December 26 and will end on
January 9.
</P>
<P>
Bands and performers from Africa, Europe, Asia, North and Latin
America, would perform each night.
</P>
<P>
The massive party is broadcast via satellite and is expected to
draw hundreds of millions of viewers, said Mustafa Asaad, president
of Public Graphic, the local advertising agency organizing the
events.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the celebrations would attract foreign investment
and promote tourism. 
</P>
