<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Leaders Express New Hopes for New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- As the new year is round the
corner, Turkish leaders pledged reforms, democracy and well-being
for the nation in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In his new year message, President Suleiman Demirel said, "
Turkey, which has proven that republic, democracy, secularism and
Islam are concepts in harmony with each other, is determined to
continue along the same path."
</P>
<P>
Noting that Turkey must keep pace with the world, the president
said, "in this light we must complete as soon as possible the
economic, political, judicial and administrative reforms that we
have begun."
</P>
<P>
The speaker of the parliament, Yildirim Akbulut, said in his new
year message that Turkey's target in the new millenium was to
become one of the world's most developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"We should make wide-spread reforms in every field, including
local administration, the judicial system, education and social
security," he said.
</P>
<P>
The speaker added: "We should revitalize relations between the
state and the people. We should enlarge our democracy and permit
the contributions of non-governmental organizations."
</P>
<P>
In his new year message, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said that
Turkey was entering the year 2000 with great hopes. Noting that the
1999 killer quakes in Turkey, which claimed the lives of tens of
thousands of people, had caused great sorrow in the country, Ecevit
promised to meet the needs of the quake victims.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the year that is passing by, the premier
underscored that it had been a successful year for Turkey in many
aspects, including reforms in the constitution and solving economic
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit also highly evaluated the fact that Turkey had taken a
big step on the way toward membership in the European Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
