<HEADLINE> CIS, Baltic States React to Yeltsin Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Boris Yeltsin's move Friday to
resign as president of Russia and handing his powers to Prime
Minister Vladimir Putin, the acting president, received positive
reactions from other former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
Noting Yeltsin's visit to Estonia in 1991, when the Russian
president advocated Estonia's independence, President Lennart Meri
of the Baltic state said Yeltsin has won a place for himself in
history.
</P>
<P>
"That (the resignation) was a courageous step, and the
Estonians will keep good impressions of it," Meri said.
</P>
<P>
He said Putin "will carry this load... as acting president, and
the future will show how easy or difficult that path is."
</P>
<P>
Belarus received Yeltsin's resignation with understanding,
President Alexander Lukashenko said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, "under whose leadership Russia has passed through the
hard way of transformation, made a courageous act which will be
worthily assessed by the current and future generations, as well
as the entire international community," Lukashenko said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that Putin, "who has done a lot for
Belarussian-Russian unification, will be consistently pursuing the
policy aimed at implementing Belarussian- Russian agreements."
</P>
<P>
In Astana, capital of Kazakhstan, Foreign Minister Yerlan
Idrisov said Yeltsin's resignation "has opened the way to renewal
and democracy."
</P>
<P>
The move was a "very well-considered step by a major politician,
who has made a sober-minded assessment of the situation in Russia,
and has opened the way for renewal and democracy," Interfax quoted
Idrisov as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Boris Nikolayevich's step is worth of praise. It is a step of
a mature statesman," he said, describing the step as " the basis
for stability" in Russia.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the next presidential election in spring
2000 would "set out a general strategy" for Russia, a way to"
prosperity, to further democratization."
</P>
<P>
A democratic path in Russia "would do nothing but good to
Kazakh-Russian relations," Idrisov said.  
</P>
