<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Decrees Security Guarantees for Yeltsin, Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Russian Acting President
Vladimir Putin on Friday signed a decree providing security
guarantees for Boris Yeltsin, who stepped down earlier in the day
as the Russian head of state.
</P>
<P>
The decree makes immediate provisions for "legal, social
security and other guarantees" for one who has left office as
president "due to the expiry of his term... or who has resigned
before such a date or who has displayed a steady inability for
health reasons to exercise his powers" and for "members of his
family."
</P>
<P>
It is reported that one of the key conditions for Yeltsin's
early resignation is the provision of security guarantees for
himself and his family after he leaves the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Putin's decree means that Yeltsin and his family members will
be exempted from criminal liabilities.
</P>
<P>
The Communist-dominated State Duma once put forward a motion in
the lower house of parliament to impeach Yeltsin for the
disintegration of the Soviet Union and his order to open fire on
the White House, former seat of the Russian parliament, in 1991.
The impeachment motion was later defeated.
</P>
<P>
There have also been media reports over the years about alleged
involvement in money-laundering and other economic scandals by
Yeltsin and his family members.
</P>
<P>
Under the Putin decree, regardless of his age, a former
president will receive a life pension equivalent to 75 percent of
the presidential salary, the Interfax news agency quoted the
Kremlin press service as saying.
</P>
<P>
If he is elected for another official position, his pension
would be suspended for the period he holds the post.
</P>
<P>
He would be provided with bodyguards both at his permanent
place of residence and during his visits, with special
telecommunications services and with means of transport.
</P>
<P>
Bodyguards would also be provided for members of his family who
live with him or accompany him.
</P>
<P>
The ex-president and members of his family who live with him
would be entitled to the same kind of medical services he had
received when still in office.
</P>
<P>
His life and his health condition would be subject to
compulsory state insurance for a sum equivalent to the annual
presidential salary.
</P>
<P>
He would be immune against prosecution, arrest, bodily search
and interrogation. His right of immunity would extend to his place
of residence, his office if he works, his vehicles, communications
means, baggage and correspondence.
</P>
<P>
After his death, every member of his family would receive a
monthly allowance equivalent to sixfold the minimum old age
pension as of his death date.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, the Kremlin announced that Alexander Voloshin,
a long-time Yeltsin aide, would continue to serve as head of the
presidential administration. Observers believe the retention of
Voloshin inside the Kremlin means that Yeltsin will continue to
exert certain influences on Russian politics in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
