<HEADLINE> Air Traffic in South America Guaranteed: OACI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Air traffic in South America
during the transition from December 31 to January 1 of 2000 is
guaranteed from the regional headquarters of the International
Civil Aviation Organization (OACI) in this city.
</P>
<P>
This statement was made Friday by OACI South America regional
office deputy director Jose Miguel Chepi, who added that together
with the Peruvian Corporation of Civil Aviation (Corpac), they
have planned to implement a high frequency radio system.
</P>
<P>
This system is independent of communications suppliers and has
the capability of operating even with electric energy faults.
</P>
<P>
Links in all the control centers of the region have been
established with these pieces of equipment and telephony systems
with satellite connection that fulfill the requirements of the
year 2000 have been implemented
</P>
<P>
Chepi said that the regional unit installed in the Corpac of
Lima, one of the seven the OACI will operate in all the world,
will supervise the supply of air navigation services and will
solve the possible problems of the region.
</P>
<P>
OACI representative Peter Cerda said that they have visited 61
international airports in South America to find possible failures
in the systems, "but we are satisfied with the work done" by all
the technicians in the team." 
</P>
</TEXT>
