<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2130 GMT, Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has stressed the
importance of enhancing Egypt's cooperation with the other
countries in the coming century when no single nation would be able
to develop on its own.
</P>
<P>
"Our relations with the world countries is strong and it will
get stronger in the future," Mubarak said on Thursday in his end-
of-the-millennium statements to the editor-in-chief of Egypt's Al-
Gomhuria daily, Samir Ragab.
</P>
<P>
"The continued development of the relations is our main concern
(as) it is impossible for any country to work alone in the future,"
the president said. (Egypt-World)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Tens of thousands of fasting Iranians from various
walks of life on Friday poured into streets throughout the country,
voicing their support for the Palestinian struggles and condemning
any compromise with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Carrying placards with pictures of the ancient al-Aqsa mosque in
Jerusalem, pictures of Iranian leaders as well as anti-Israel and
anti-U.S. slogans, the demonstrators in the Iranian capital marched
from six predetermined routes to Tehran University, where the
Friday prayer congregations are held. (Iran-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid
on Friday urged Iraq to take creative steps in a bid to help heal
the rifts in the Arab world in the coming new era.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued hours before the advent of the third
millennium, Abdel-Meguid spoke of the major events that occurred in
the Arab world this century and the 22-nation pan-Arab forum's
expectations and hopes.
</P>
<P>
He singled out one momentous event in the last decade: Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait on August 2, 1990, which, he regretted, had a
clear negative impact on Arab solidarity and incised a deep wound
in inter-Arab relations still felt till now.
</P>
<P>
Such rifts should be remedied through creative overtures and
well-calculated concessions by Iraq, the AL chief said. (Arab
League-Millennium Statement) 
</P>
