<HEADLINE> Mandela Lights Flame of Hope for New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela, who has come to symbolize South Africa's
victory over racism and oppression, on Friday lit a symbolic flame
of hope for the new millennium in his former prison cell on Robben
Island.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony watched by only a handful of people, he handed
the flame to President Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
The handover, which will be televised at midnight, was one of
the highlights of a multi-million and millennium celebration for
some 500 VIP guests on the island.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who helicoptered in with Mbeki just before 9.30 p.m.,
was earlier greeted with a standing ovation when he entered the
specially-erected marquee next to the island's airstrip.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming them, Public Enterprises Minister Jeff Radebe
described Mandela as one of Africa's greatest sons.
</P>
<P>
Radebe, the Cabinet minister tasked with overseeing the
official millennium celebrations, said that as the light on
leadership was carried on into a new era, Mbeki symbolized the
rise of the African continent. 
</P>
