<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Year At Record Highs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks celebrated
the year-end session with a full slate of records Friday in
confidence that the world financial markets would be free from the
Y2K problem when Year 2000 is rolling in.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 44.26 at 11,497.12,
surpassing the record closing high of 11,484.66 points set
Wednesday. The session ended at 1 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index rose 4.78 at a new high of 1,469.25 and the
technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 32.44 at 4.069.31,
topping the record high of 4.041.46 points set Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The great performance put the Dow's year-end rally at 25.2
percent and the S&AMP;P index gained 19.5 percent in the year. The
Nasdaq index emerged as the biggest winner with the gain of 85.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied today as Japan, South Korea and Australia
reported no major troubles with their computers when the new year
rolled in. The positive indications convinced investors that
financial markets in the United States and Europe will enter the
new millennium unscathed by computer malfunctions because the
United States and Europe have spent far more money to deal with
the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected resignation by Russian president Boris Yeltsin
had little impact on the Wall Street stocks.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 3.09 at 650.30 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 10.85 at 876.97. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 8.16 at 504.75.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-3 margin, with
2,172 up, 937 down and 419 unchanged on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 372.60 million shears at the close of half-
day trading, down from 533.10 million in the previous full session.
</P>
</TEXT>
