<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief hails Peaceful End to Hijacking of Indian Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan was greatly relieved that the hijacking of an Indian
plane ended peacefully without further loss of life, U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is particularly pleased that the
passengers and the crew of the hijacked plane are back in freedom,
" the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General reiterates his condemnation of all acts
of terrorism, from whatever quarter," said Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
The 154 passengers and crew were freed at Kandahar airport, in
Afghanistan, after a week-long ordeal. They were released after
India freed three jailed kashmiri militants.
</P>
<P>
The hijackers freed 28 other passengers last weekend when the
plane landed in the United Arab Emirates. They also handed over
the body of a passenger they stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, a U.N. humanitarian official, Eric
de Maul, tried to ease the discomfort of the passengers while they
were being held hostage by supplying washing materials and flying
in meals from Islamabad, Pakistan, when supplies in kandahar ran
low. 
</P>
</TEXT>
