<HEADLINE> No Vacuum of Power in Russia: Putin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 31 (Xinhua) -- There will be no "vacuum of
power" in Russia "for a minute or even a second" after ex-
president Boris Yeltsin's resignation, said Russian Acting
President Vladimir Putin in his New Year address to the nation on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Any attempt to overstep the federal Constitution will be cut
short resolutely" and the Russians will be able to exercise all
their rights, Putin said in the televised address.
</P>
<P>
Boris Yeltsin's decision to resign as Russian President "
completely conformed to the Constitution" and "It will be possible
only after a while to give a proper assessment of what he has done
for Russia in the last few years," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
The military, border guard and other security services would
continue to fight "terrorists," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The freedom of speech, worship and press, the property rights -
-these fundamental elements of civilized society -- will be
reliably protected by the state. The Armed Forces, the Federal
Border Service,the law-enforcement bodies are working in a regular
regime. The state has guarded and will continue guarding the
security of every person,"said the acting president.  
</P>
