<HEADLINE> U.N. Waiting for Annexes to Iraqi Distribution Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard said on Friday that the United Nations is waiting for
annexes to Iraqi distribution plan and the distribution plan has
yet to be submitted in full.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was responding to questions in recent days about
when the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan would endorse the
distribution plan for phase seven of the oil-for-food programme.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accused the U.N. chief on Thursday of delaying approval
of a foodstuff distribution plan for the current phase of Iraq's
oil-for-food deal with the world body.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said the United Nations has received the executive
summary and the proposed allocations by sector, but the Government
of Iraq has yet to submit the annexes to the distribution plan.
</P>
<P>
The annexes list all the items that Iraq intends to procure
under relevant U.N. resolution and they have to be reviewed by the
U.N. Secretariat before the Secretary-General can approve the plan,
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
On December 10, 1999, the United Nations Security Council
unanimously approved a six-month extension of the humanitarian
programme after weeks of haggling about future policy towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The programme, which began to be implemented in late 1996, is
aimed to ease the humanitarian crisis in Iraq caused by the
stringent U.N. sanctions which have been in place since Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait in 1990. The sanctions cannot be lifted after
Iraq was clarified that it has destroyed all its weapons of mass
destruction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991231.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Analysis: Yeltsin Leaves Kremlin a More Satisfied Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 31 (Xinhua) -- For months, the question on
Yeltsin's resignation as Russian president has been when rather
than why.
</P>
<P>
He took that step Friday, concluding the Yeltsin era with yet
another political surprise, although rumors about his step-down
had been flying around for some time.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, Yeltsin had sent shock waves, firing
top aides and prime minister after prime minister in political
maneuvers aimed at strengthening his faltering position.
</P>
<P>
The idea of vacating the Kremlin for a preferred successor
surfaced in Russian press even before Yeltsin picked Vladimir
Putin to replace Yevgeny Primakov, the fourth prime minister to be
sacked in a little over one year, in August.
</P>
<P>
However, political developments later, such as the widely
reported scandal implicating Yeltsin, his family members and close
aides, made it hard for him to take such a move.
</P>
<P>
But this time around, as the world moves to the year 2000, the
going becomes much easier to Yeltsin: his favored political forces
have made a strong showing in the parliamentary elections on
December 19; Putin, his anointed successor, is by far the most
popular politician in post-Soviet Russia.
</P>
<P>
In addition, right after the resignation announcement, Putin
signed a decree providing for "legal, social security and other
guarantees" for Yeltsin and his family members.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that one of the key conditions for Yeltsin's
early resignation is the provision of security guarantees for
himself and his family after he leaves the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
The Communist-dominated State Duma once put forward a motion in
the lower house of parliament to impeach Yeltsin for the
disintegration of the Soviet Union and his order to open fire on
the White House, former seat of the Russian parliament, in 1991.
The impeachment motion was later defeated.
</P>
<P>
There have also been media reports over the years about alleged
involvement in money laundering and other economic scandals by
Yeltsin, his family members and close aides.
</P>
<P>
Putin's decree means that Yeltsin and his family members will
be exempted from criminal liabilities.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, the emergence of a more pro-government State
Duma and the mounting popularity of Putin enabled Yeltsin to leave
the Kremlin contently.
</P>
<P>
"When I saw how much hope and faith was pinned on a new
generation of politicians at the elections to the State Duma, I
realized that I have fulfilled the main task of my life. Russia
will never go back to the past. Russia will always move forward
now," Yeltsin told the nation in a televised address.
</P>
<P>
"I should not be in the way of the natural course of history.
What's the point of holding on to power when the country has a
strong man worthy to be president and on whom practically every
citizen of Russia pins his hopes for the future now," he said,
referring to Putin.
</P>
<P>
Putin's approval rating skyrocketed amid a popular military
campaign against rebels in the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
By and large, Putin will be the biggest gainer of Yeltsin's
resignation. As acting president, he now enjoys media coverage
unrivaled by his opponents.
</P>
<P>
With the next presidential elections moved up by three months
March, the other contestants for the Kremlin now have even less
time to prepare for the race.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin became president of Russia in 1991 and during the past
few years, he had been dogged by health problems such as
respiratory and heart ailments.
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin denied health as the reason that led to his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
"I am leaving not for health reasons, but because of the knot
of problems," he said. "A new generation is coming to replace me.
The generation of those who can do much more and do it better."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
